1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 Qf6 6. Qd2 dxc6 {This is another typical opening variation (Scotch Opening) where Black accepts to give to his opponent a healthy majority in return for quick development and good piece placement.} 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Qf4 {Relying on his better pawn structure, White aims for the endgame.} Be6 {Black must play as energetically as possible. In the Scotch, White invests time (moving the king's knight twice) to gain a structural advantage. White has the better pawn structure but in return, Black has a lead in development.} ({The previous try was} 8... Ng6 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {, but it seems that the text move appears to be rather good. White anyway will be forced to exchange queens and Black will get even quicker development than in case of 8...Ng6.}) 9. Qxf6 gxf6 {It seems that Black has gone astray; he did not only double his queenside pawns but he also ruined his kingside pawns too! But in reality, he will soon play ...f5.} 10. f4 (10. Na4 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 O-O-O+ 13. Bd3 b6 {, seems rather satisfactory for Black.}) 10... f5 11. Bd2 ({White rejected} 11. Na4 $6 {, because of} Bd4 $1 12. c3 {( 12.e5 a6! )} Bg7 13. Nc5 fxe4 14. Nxe4 O-O-O 15. Kf2 Rhe8 $15 {.}) 11... O-O-O 12. O-O-O {If White manages to consolidate by developing the f1-bishop and h1-rook, he will have the advantage.} Rhg8 13. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gf1d3]} h5 $5 {Black has to use his lead in development by opening the position. He still has a positional disadvantage so his chances lay in active play. Now White opts for a forced line that at the end of all leads to draw.} 14. Bh3 (14. Be2 h4 15. gxh4 Rg2 $1 {, promises good compensation for the pawn.}) 14... h4 {Shirov constantly poses Anand problems. How would you handle the pressure on g3?} 15. Na4 $1 {Now it looks like Black is in danger as his f5-pawn is going to be hanging.} Bf2 16. Bb4 {Na4 forced the bishop off the a3-f8 diagonal. Now the e7-knight is attacked, which in turn defends the f5-pawn. e7 and f5 are hanging. How do you solve this concrete problem?} Rxd1+ $1 17. Rxd1 (17. Kxd1 hxg3 18. hxg3 Kd8 {is also OK.} 19. Bxe7+ $6 {White shouldn't give up the bishop pair unless there is an immediate benefit.} Kxe7 20. exf5 $2 Bd5 $17 21. Rf1 Bxg3 {Black regains the pawn, has the bishop pair and far superior pawn structure.}) 17... hxg3 18. hxg3 (18. Bxe7 $2 gxh2 {.}) 18... b5 $1 {Resourceful aggression. The e7-knight still couldn't move because f5 was attacked. ...b5 also creates an escape square for the king.} (18... Rxg3 $4 19. Bxe7 Rxh3 20. Rd8#) 19. Bxe7 bxa4 20. Bxf5 ({It was important to notice in advance that after} 20. exf5 {, Black has} Bxa2 {.}) 20... Bxf5 21. exf5 Be3+ {White's king is forced into the corner.} 22. Kb1 Rxg3 {Black is not in danger of losing anymore.} 23. Rd8+ Kb7 24. a3 Bxf4 25. Rf8 Be5 26. Z0 ({The players agreed to a draw because of the repetition} 26. Rxf7 Rg1+ 27. Ka2 Rg2 28. Kb1 Rg1+ {. A short but interesting battle.}) 1/2-1/2

