1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 Nxc3 4. dxc3 d6 5. Nf3 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nxe5 {Probably this cannot be considered a strong set-up against the 'Alekhine Defence'. Already Black has put the bases for a successful ending; the only thing he has to do is to exchange pieces and his majority will easily tell. Well, nothing is as easy as it looks by the way!} Ke8 8. Bc4 e6 9. f4 Nd7 10. Nf3 ({This looks a bit better than} 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 11. Be3 Bd6 12. O-O Ke7 13. Rae1 Rhe8 14. Bd3 f5 15. c4 b6 16. Bd4 Kf7 $15 {Sarapu, O-Hort, V Sousse 1967, or StartFENr1b1kb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/4N3/2B2P2/2P5/PPP3PP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 1 10EndFEN 10.Nd3 Bd6 11.Be3 Nb6 12.Bb3 Nd5 13.Bxd5 exd5 $15 Ivanov, V-Gerchikov,M St Petersburg 1997.}) 10... Bd6 11. Bd2 Ke7 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Rde1 Kf8 {The 'castle' is completed! It's true that White has a couple of extra tempi, but as Black's position is very solid he can't take any advantage of this fact.} 14. Rhf1 h6 ({Black avoided the drawish continuation} 14... Nf6 15. Ne5 b6 16. Bb5 Rd8 17. Nc6 Re8 18. Ne5 {. This is fair enough to prove to us the validity of Black's position; he can choose either to draw or to try for more.}) 15. g4 Nb6 $6 ({A better way for Black to develop his pieces starts with} 15... a6 {.}) 16. Bd3 Bd7 17. Ne5 Rad8 18. h4 $1 ({Other options, such as} 18. Nxd7+ $6 Nxd7 19. h4 Nc5 20. g5 Nxd3+ 21. cxd3 h5 {, can be good only for Black. But now suddenly White has created a strong initiative on the kingside and Black is obliged to take measures against it.}) 18... Kg8 19. g5 hxg5 20. fxg5 (20. hxg5 Bxe5 21. fxe5 g6 {( 21...Bc6?! 22.g6 fxg6 23.Bxg6 Rf8 24.Bg5 $16 )} 22. c4 $13 {, was also good and interesting. Black's majority on the kingside is balanced by the white bishop pair.}) 20... Bxe5 21. Rxe5 Bc6 22. h5 (22. c4 Nd7 23. Re3 Nc5 {, was about equal.}) 22... Rd5 23. Re2 ({After} 23. Rxd5 $5 Bxd5 24. b3 e5 {, both sides seem to have chances.}) 23... Bb5 $1 {Of course! Exchanging pieces (especially a part of the dangerous white bishop pair) should be Black's first and most important priority.} 24. Bxb5 Rxb5 25. h6 (25. b3 {, is a logical alternative. After} Nc8 26. c4 Rc5 {, all results are possible.}) 25... Nc4 26. h7+ {The safest way to equality.} (26. Rh1 $6 Rd8 {( 26...Nxd2 27.h7+ Kh8 28.Rxd2 Rd5 $15 )} 27. h7+ Kh8 $17 {.}) 26... Kxh7 27. Rxf7 Rd8 $1 (27... c6 $6 28. b3 Nxd2 29. Rxd2 Rxg5 30. Rxb7 $14 {.}) 28. Rxc7 Rxd2 29. Rxd2 Nxd2 30. Kxd2 Rxb2 {Black kept his 'extra' pawn all game long. In the meantime, White has succeeded in keeping his pieces active and he should have no real problem to achieve the draw.} 31. a4 Kg6 32. Rc5 $6 {The first of a series of inaccurate moves. In this ending White makes one 'mistake' after another and finally manages to lose this position.} (32. c4 e5 {( 32...Kxg5 33.Rxg7+ Kf4 34.Kd3 a5 35.c5= )} 33. Kd3 Kxg5 34. Rxg7+ Kf6 35. Rc7 Ke6 36. c5 {, was the simplest.}) 32... Rb6 33. c4 $6 ({Accepting the mistake of the previous move with} 33. Rc7 {, was not a shame but a must!}) 33... Rc6 $1 34. Re5 (34. Ra5 a6 35. Kd3 Kh5 36. Re5 Kg4 $15 {.}) 34... Rxc4 35. Rxe6+ Kxg5 36. Re7 g6 37. Rxb7 Rxa4 {Black has won a pawn but the position still remains drawish.} 38. Kd3 Kf6 39. c4 g5 40. c5 Ra6 41. Kd4 g4 42. Kd5 g3 43. c6 (43. Rb3 $1 g2 44. Rg3 Ra2 45. c6 Rd2+ 46. Kc5 Ke6 47. Rg6+ Kf5 48. Rg8 {, was simpler.}) 43... g2 44. Rb1 Ke7 45. Re1+ $2 ({The losing move. White could have been very near to his target after} 45. Rb7+ Kf6 {( 45...Kd8 46.Rg7 Ra2 47.Kc5 Rb2 48.Rg8+= )} 46. Rb1 Ra2 47. c7 Rc2 48. Rg1 {.}) 45... Kd8 46. Kd6 Rb6 $1 {Probably White missed this strong move.} 47. Rg1 Rb2 48. Re1 Rd2+ 49. Kc5 Rf2 50. Rg1 (50. Kd6 Rf6+ 51. Kc5 Rf1 {.}) 50... Kc7 51. Kd5 (51. Kb5 a6+ 52. Kc5 Rf5+ 53. Kd4 Rg5 54. Ke4 Kxc6 {.}) 51... a5 52. Kc5 a4 0-1

