1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {This is one of the earliest disputes in the theory of doubled pawns and pawn majorities; the 'Exchange Variation' of the 'Ruy Lopez'. This opening often leads to queenless middle game, pitting White's static advantage (his opponent's doubled c-pawns which give him a healthy majority on the kingside) against Black's dynamic ones (the bishop pair and an extra semi-open file).} Bd7 8. Be3 O-O-O 9. Nd2 ({Another line is} 9. Nc3 Re8 10. O-O-O Bb4 11. Nde2 f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 {Smyslov-Keres, Moscow 1940.}) 9... Ne7 10. O-O-O f6 {White dreams of a pawn ending but there is a serious problem that stops his dream; Black will not cooperate, by avoiding pointless exchanges.} 11. f3 Ng6 12. h4 h5 13. Nc4 c5 {Black is using his doubled pawns for gaining space and generally restricts White's pieces.} 14. Nf5 (14. Ne2 $6 Bb5 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. b3 Bxc4 17. bxc4 Ne5 {, cannot be advisable.}) 14... Be6 $5 (14... Bxf5 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. exf5 Ne7 17. Bxc5 Nxf5 {, would be OK for Black, who is seeking something more.}) 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Nd2 b6 17. b3 Kc8 18. Bf2 Nf4 19. g3 g6 $1 20. Ne7+ ({Maybe} 20. gxf4 gxf5 21. Rg1 Kd7 $13 {, was preferable.}) 20... Bxe7 21. gxf4 f5 22. Rg1 Rg8 23. Nc4 Bf6 24. a4 Kb7 25. Rg2 Bxc4 ({Leading to equality. If Black wanted to continue, he should have opted for} 25... fxe4 26. fxe4 Bg4 27. e5 Bd8 28. Ne3 $13 {.}) 26. bxc4 Rg7 27. Kb1 Bc3 28. Ka2 Re7 29. Kb3 Bh8 30. e5 $1 (30. Rxg6 $6 fxe4 31. fxe4 Rxe4 32. Rh6 {( 32.f5?! Rf4 $17 )} Bg7 33. Rxh5 Rxf4 $15 {.}) 30... Re6 31. Rg1 Bg7 32. Rd1 Kc8 33. a5 Bh6 34. Be3 Bf8 35. Ra1 Kb7 36. Rd1 Be7 37. Bf2 Kc8 38. Ra1 Kb7 39. Rd1 Kc8 40. Ra1 Kb7 41. Rd1 1/2-1/2

