1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {The fashionable 'Berlin Wall' promises White a long-term lasting advantage due to his kingside pawn majority but on the other hand gives Black easy development, the bishop pair and not so many tactical dangers in general.} 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. h3 Be7 {Highly unusual. Normally Black avoids exchanging the darksquared bishops but here he invites it wholeheartedly.} 11. Bg5 {The thematic response.} (11. Bf4 Be6 12. g4 Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. Kg2 Be7 15. a3 Rd8 16. Rad1 h5 {, was seen in Jenni, F-Mantovani,R Switzerland 1999.}) 11... Bxg5 {Black's idea is to place his king on e7, connecting the rooks and then to contain the white majority along the diagonal h3-c8.} (11... Bb4 $5 {, is interesting:} 12. Ne4 Be6 13. c3 Bf8 14. g4 Ne7 15. Nd4 Bd5 16. Nd2 c5 17. Nb5 Kd7 18. Bf4 Kc6 $13 {Van den Doel-Miles, Groningen 1997.}) 12. Nxg5 h6 13. Nge4 b6 14. Rfd1 (14. Rad1 Ba6 15. Rfe1 Ke7 {, seems OK for Black.}) 14... Ne7 ({Now} 14... Ba6 15. a4 $1 {, is a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 15. f4 Ng6 16. Rf1 h5 17. Rae1 Bf5 18. Ng3 Ne7 $1 {Cautious play.} (18... Bxc2 $6 {, allows White to expand his majority:} 19. f5 Nf8 20. Rf2 Bd3 21. e6 $13 {.}) 19. Nxf5 Nxf5 20. Kf2 Nd4 21. Rc1 ({White could think of} 21. Rd1 $5 Rd8 {( 21...Nxc2?! 22.Rd2 Nb4 23.Rfd1 $16 )} 22. Rd2 $14 {.}) 21... Rd8 22. Rfd1 Ke7 23. Ne4 ({White would love to play} 23. g3 {, keeping his majority alive, but Black can continue} f6 24. exf6+ gxf6 25. Ne2 c5 26. c3 Nf5 {, with a satisfactory position.}) 23... h4 $1 24. b4 Rh5 $2 ({Black blunders. The simplest was} 24... Nf5 25. a4 f6 26. exf6+ gxf6 {.}) 25. Ng5 $2 ({Both players seem to have missed a rather simple combination:} 25. g4 $1 Rhh8 {( 25...hxg3+? 26.Nxg3 Rxh3 27.Rxd4 Rxd4 28.Nf5++- )} 26. f5 {, with a tremendous position for White. No doubt, G.Kasparov would have won this and shaken a few ghosts from his shoulders at the same time.}) 25... Rhh8 (25... f6 $6 26. c3 fxg5 27. cxd4 gxf4 28. Rxc6 $16 {.}) 26. Rd3 Ne6 27. Nxe6 Kxe6 28. Rcd1 Rd5 29. c4 Rxd3 30. Rxd3 a5 $1 {Black immediately creates counterplay on the other side and he has little to fear from White's limited kingside majority.} 31. bxa5 Ra8 $6 (31... bxa5 $1 {, was simpler:} 32. Ra3 {( 32.Rb3 Kf5 33.Ke3 Re8 34.Rb7 g5 35.fxg5 Rxe5+ 36.Kd3 Ke6! 37.Rxc7 Rxg5 38.Rxc6+ Kd7 39.Rf6 Rxg2 40.Rxf7+ Ke6= )} Rb8 33. Rxa5 Rb4 34. Rc5 Kd7 35. f5 Ra4 36. e6+ fxe6 37. fxe6+ Kxe6 38. Rxc6+ Ke5 39. Rxc7 Rxa2+ 40. Kg1 Ra1+ 41. Kh2 Rc1 {.}) 32. Ra3 Kf5 $1 33. Kf3 Ra6 $1 34. c5 $1 f6 $2 {A nearly losing move.} (34... bxc5 35. Ke3 $14 {, was Black's only continuation.}) 35. Re3 $1 Rxa5 36. e6 Ra8 37. e7 Re8 38. a4 $1 Kg6 39. Re6 Kf7 40. Rxc6 $2 (40. f5 $1 {, was the right path:} Rxe7 41. Rxc6 Rd7 {( 41...bxc5?! 42.a5+- )} 42. cxb6 cxb6 43. Rxb6 $16 {.}) 40... Ra8 $1 {But now Black saves the day!} 41. cxb6 cxb6 42. Rxb6 Rxa4 43. Re6 Ke8 44. Re4 Ra3+ 45. Re3 Rxe3+ 46. Kxe3 f5 1/2-1/2

