17... Kf7 {[%mdl 32768]} 18. g3 {This is a notorious endgame, where Black usually keeps the draw, as it is not easy for White to benefit by her kingside healthy pawn majority. A good analysis of this ending (in general) can be found in FIDE/TRG Yearbook 2010, by Alexander Beliavsky. White's plan is to play h3, g4 and f4 and activate the king with Kg2-f3-e4.} ({Starting with} 18. f4 $2 {is a mistake - not only because the king is pushed into the corner with} Bc5+ 19. Kh1 {, but also because Black can play} h4 {followed by ...Kg6 and put the king on f5 and possibly even e4.}) 18... Bb4 19. Kg2 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gf3e4] The white king must be activated on e4. Next, the pawn majority can be activated with h3, g4 and f4-f5.} *

