{The next game was played in the semifinal phase of the FIDE Women World Championship 2010, and it gave Hou Yifan the ticket to the final, where she was able to win it, becoming the FIDE Women World Champion. As the event was held in Turkish territory, it was closely analysed in our sessions with the Turkish National Men Team - I was the National Coach from 2006 to 2012. Many of the 'discoveries' were made by my trainees, who were trying to dig deep enough to understand and master all subtleties of the ending. Our team-work was containing all parts of a game; opening, middlegame and endgame. But we were mostly concentrating on the transition from the middlegame to the endgame and we were able to discover and analyse many more similar games than the three presented here. I am sure that the Chinese prodigy and FIDE Women World Champion, Hou Yifan, had a good knowledge of the two supplementary games. Maybe she couldn't remember exactly the moves, but… She walked known paths and repeated what it had to be done. I am sorry to disappointed you readers, but a professional game of chess has very little to do with fantasy!} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Ke8 10. Ne2 Be7 11. b3 a5 12. a4 Be6 13. Bb2 h5 14. Nfd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Rd8 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rad1 Kf7 {This is a notorious endgame, where Black usually keeps the draw, as it is not easy for White to benefit by her kingside healthy pawn majority. A good analysis of this ending (in general) can be found in FIDE/TRG Yearbook 2010, by Alexander Beliavsky.} 18. g3 Bb4 19. Kg2 {The white king must be activated on e4.} Bd2 20. Kf3 Rd5 21. Ke2 {But first has to defend some vulnerable spots!} Rhd8 22. c4 R5d7 23. Bc1 Bc3 (23... Bxc1 {, is good enough for the draw:} 24. Rxd7+ Rxd7 25. Rxc1 Kg6 $1 {.}) 24. Rxd7+ Rxd7 25. f4 g6 $2 ({This is really passive. With the active} 25... Kg6 $1 {, Black would have limited trouble to hold the draw:} 26. h3 Kf5 27. g4+ hxg4 28. hxg4+ Ke4 {.}) 26. Rf3 Bb4 27. Rd3 $1 Rxd3 28. Kxd3 Be7 {H.Koneru thought that this position was solid enough for a draw, but White has a kingside majority, more space, and a more active king. Keeping the king passive with 25...g6?, was not a good idea.} 29. Be3 c5 (29... b6 {, looks solid enough and although Black will suffer for a long time, her chances to draw seems to be rather good. But this is not the case! After} 30. c5 $1 Bd8 {( 30...b5 31.b4+- )} 31. h3 Ke8 32. g4 hxg4 33. hxg4 Kf7 34. Ke4 Ke8 35. f5 gxf5+ 36. gxf5 exf5+ {( 36...Kf7 37.f6 Kg6 38.Kf4 Kh6 39.Kg4+ Kg6 40.Bd2+- )} 37. Kxf5 b5 {( 37...Kd7 38.e6+ Ke8 39.Bd4 b5 40.b4+- )} 38. Bd2 b4 39. Bxb4 $1 axb4 40. Ke4 Kd7 41. Kd4 Bg5 42. a5 Kc8 43. Kc4 {, White wins as well.}) 30. Ke4 b6 31. Kf3 Bf8 32. g4 ({White makes her life more difficult! Good training means to know well how to win technical positions:} 32. h3 $1 Be7 33. g4 Bf8 34. Ke4 {and now: a) b)} hxg4 {(If Black refrains from capturing in g4 with 34...Be7 , then White wins by 35.gxh5 gxh5 36.f5 c6 37.Bc1 Bh4 38.Bh6! (a position from the game Howell-Parker, Nottingham 2005) 38...Ke7 ( 38...Be1 39.Bg5+- ) 39.Kf4 Kd7 40.Bf8 Be1 41.Kg5 Bg3 42.Kf6+- .)} 35. hxg4 Be7 36. Bf2 $1 {( 36.f5? gxf5+ 37.gxf5 Bh4 38.Kf4 Be1! , gives Black counterplay).} Bd8 37. Kf3 Be7 38. Kg3 Bd8 39. Kh3 c6 {( 39...Be7 40.Bh4+- )} 40. Bh4 Bc7 41. Bf6 Kg8 42. Kh4 Kf7 43. Kg5 b5 44. Kh6 $1 {(a winning plan that was first seen in Dominguez, C-Visconti,E Buenos Aires 1959)} Bb6 45. Kh7 Bc7 46. Bh4 $1 Bb6 47. Bf2 bxa4 48. bxa4 Ba7 49. g5 Bb6 50. Be3 Ba7 51. f5 $1 exf5 52. Bf4 Bb6 53. e6+ Kxe6 54. Kxg6 {.}) 32... Be7 33. Kg3 c6 34. Kh3 Bd8 35. Bf2 $1 {The typical plan; the white bishop must occupy the h1-d8 diagonal in order to attack the black queenside pawn base on b6.} Bc7 36. Bh4 hxg4+ (36... Ke8 37. Bf6 Kf7 38. Kh4 {, makes no difference.}) 37. Kxg4 Kg7 38. Bf6+ Kf7 39. Bh4 Kg7 40. Bf6+ Kf7 41. Kg5 b5 {The only move. If the black king moves she loses the g6-pawn and if the bishop moves then 42.Bd8, follows. Black has now at her disposal the moves ...Bb6-c7, but the black queenside pawns become vulnerable.} 42. Kh6 bxa4 43. bxa4 Bb6 44. Be7 $2 ({Correct idea but wrong execution! Before she goes for this trick, she should have inserted} 44. h4 $1 {, an important tempo as can be seen by the analysis:} Bc7 45. Kh7 Bb6 46. Be7 $1 Kxe7 {( 46...Ba7 47.Bd8+- )} 47. Kxg6 Kf8 {( 47...Bd8 48.Kg7+- )} 48. h5 Bd8 49. h6 Kg8 50. h7+ Kh8 51. Kf7 Kxh7 52. Kxe6 Kg7 53. Kd6 {.}) 44... Bc7 $2 ({And Black immediately returns the favour! She should have captured the bishop and with some precise moves to secure the draw:} 44... Kxe7 $1 45. Kxg6 Bd8 46. h4 Kf8 47. h5 Kg8 48. h6 {( 48.f5 exf5 49.Kxf5 Kg7 50.Ke6 Bc7= )} Bh4 49. h7+ Kh8 50. Kf7 Kxh7 51. Kxe6 Kg7 52. Kd7 Kf8 53. e6 {( 53.f5 Bg3 54.e6 Bh4 55.Kxc6 Kg7! ( 55...Be7? 56.Kb5 Bd8 57.Kxc5 Ke7 58.Kd5! Kf6 59.c5+- ) 56.Kxc5 Be7+ 57.Kb5 Kf6= )} Bf6 54. f5 Be7 55. Kxc6 Kg7 56. Kb6 Kf6 57. Kxa5 Kxf5 58. Kb6 Bd8+ {( 58...Kxe6? 59.Kc7+- )} 59. Kxc5 Kxe6 60. Kb5 Kd7 61. a5 Bxa5 62. Kxa5 Kc6 {.}) 45. Bxc5 Bd8 46. Bf2 Be7 47. c5 $1 Bf8+ 48. Kg5 Be7+ 49. Kg4 Ke8 50. Be1 Bxc5 ({Black has no real option. The alternative} 50... Bd8 {, loses to} 51. Bh4 Bc7 52. Bf6 Kf7 53. Kg5 Bb8 54. Bd8 Ba7 55. Bb6 {.}) 51. Bxa5 Be7 52. Kf3 (52. h4 Kf7 53. Bd2 Bd8 54. a5 Bc7 55. h5 Kg7 56. hxg6 Kxg6 57. f5+ $1 exf5+ 58. Kf4 Bd8 59. a6 Bb6 60. Bc3 {, also wins. But White is in no hurry; she can afford to play around!}) 52... Kd7 53. Ke4 c5 54. Kd3 Kc6 55. Kc4 Bh4 56. Bd2 Bf2 57. h3 Bg1 58. Bc1 (58. f5 {, is another tactical win:} gxf5 {( 58...exf5 59.e6 Bh2 60.a5+- )} 59. h4 Bh2 60. h5 Bxe5 61. h6 f4 62. a5 f3 63. Be3 {. But no need for ‘complications’ anymore…}) 58... Bf2 59. Bd2 Bg1 60. Kd3 Bf2 61. Be3 Be1 62. Kc4 Bb4 63. Bf2 Kb6 64. Be3 Kc6 65. Bg1 Kb6 66. Bf2 Kc6 67. Bh4 Bd2 68. Bg5 Be1 69. Be7 Bf2 ({The alternative 'defence' was} 69... Bb4 {, when White wins by} 70. Bf8 $1 {( 70.Bd8 Bd2! )} Kb6 71. Bd6 $1 Kc6 72. Be7 Kb6 73. a5+ $1 Kxa5 {( 73...Bxa5 74.Bd8++- )} 74. Bxc5 Bd2 75. Bd4 $1 Bxf4 76. Kc5 {.}) 70. a5 Be3 71. Bg5 Bf2 72. h4 Bg3 73. a6 Bf2 74. h5 $1 gxh5 75. f5 exf5 76. e6 Bg3 77. e7 Kd7 78. a7 1-0

