{The early activity of using a pawn majority in the opening can sometimes easily backfire. And this is quite natural, as development and central control are far more important than in any other stage of the game…} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bg5+ Ke8 10. Nc3 h6 11. Bd2 Be6 12. Ne2 Rd8 13. Bc3 Be7 14. Ned4 c5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Rad1 Kf7 17. g4 Nh4 18. Nxh4 Bxh4 19. f4 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rd8 21. Rxd8 Bxd8 22. Kg2 g6 23. Kf3 c6 24. Bd2 h5 25. h3 hxg4+ 26. hxg4 a6 {This is one of the oldest examples of this type of endgame in the databases.} 27. c4 $1 {Common sense was honoured in 1959!} b5 28. b3 b4 29. Be3 Bb6 30. Bf2 Ke7 31. Bh4+ Kf7 32. Bf6 Bc7 33. Kg3 Bb6 34. Kf2 Kf8 35. Kf1 Kf7 36. Kg1 Kf8 37. Kh2 Kf7 38. Kh3 Kf8 39. Kh4 (39. Kh4 {Now Black suddenly resigned and we were denied watching the straightford winning plan. It might be something like:} Kf7 40. Kg5 Bc7 41. Kh6 Bb6 42. Bh4 Bc7 43. Bf2 Bb6 44. Kh7 Ba7 45. g5 $1 Bb6 46. Bg1 Ba7 47. f5 $1 exf5 48. e6+ Kxe6 49. Kxg6 Bb8 50. Kh7 Be5 51. g6 f4 52. g7 Bxg7 53. Kxg7 f3 54. Kf8 Ke5 55. Ke7 Ke4 56. Kd6 Kd3 57. Kxc6 Kc2 58. Kxc5 Kb2 59. Kxb4 {.}) 1-0

