{Considering White's rapid queenside majority advancement and the general advice to focus on development and castling at this early stage, what should be Black's response?} 12... Nc6 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} 13. Bg2 ({Forced. In case of} 13. b5 $2 {, White bitterly found out that after} Ne5 $1 {he was plain lost:} 14. f4 Nf3+ 15. Kf2 Bxc5+ 16. Kxf3 d4 17. Na4 Qd5+ 18. Kf2 d3+ 19. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Nd4 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Ne4+ 22. Kf3 Qd5 23. Qxd3 Nd2+ 24. Kf2 Nxb1 {0-1 Narva-Schandorff, Tallinn 1989.}) 13... Rb8 $1 14. Bf4 ({Not advisable. White had to either opt for} 14. b5 Bxc5 $1 15. bxc6 Rxb1 16. Nxb1 Qb6 17. Nbc3 Bxf2+ 18. Kf1 Ba6 19. Bf3 Rc8 20. Kg2 Rxc6 $13 {as in Siedentopf-Dickhoff, Dresden 2003,}) ({or for} 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Nd7 16. Qd3 axb4 17. axb4 Ne5 $13 {Zaja-Jukic, Solin 1993,}) ({or, finally, for} 14. Qa4 axb4 15. axb4 {( 15.Qxc6? Bd7-+ )} Bd7 16. b5 Ne5 17. Qd4 Bxc5 18. Qxe5 Bxf2+ 19. Kf1 Ba7 20. Bf3 Qb6 21. Nd1 Bxb5 $13 {Lugovoi-Womacka, Hamburg 2001. Black should be happy with the opening outcome as he can have too early his equal share of potential success.}) 14... axb4 $1 {An excellent exchange sacrifice.} *

