1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. a3 Be7 8. c5 O-O 9. g3 b6 10. b4 bxc5 11. dxc5 a5 12. Rb1 {White has taken a quick 'advantage' of his queenside majority, threatening to finish-off Black in no time. But in such an early stage it is general more advisable to be concern on the development and castling.} Nc6 $1 13. Bg2 ({Forced. In case of} 13. b5 $2 {, White bitterly found out that after} Ne5 $1 {he was plain lost:} 14. f4 Nf3+ 15. Kf2 Bxc5+ 16. Kxf3 d4 17. Na4 Qd5+ 18. Kf2 d3+ 19. Nxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Nd4 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Ne4+ 22. Kf3 Qd5 23. Qxd3 Nd2+ 24. Kf2 Nxb1 {0-1 Narva-Schandorff, Tallinn 1989.}) 13... Rb8 $1 14. Bf4 $2 ({Not advisable. White had to either opt for} 14. b5 Bxc5 $1 15. bxc6 Rxb1 16. Nxb1 Qb6 17. Nbc3 Bxf2+ 18. Kf1 Ba6 19. Bf3 Rc8 20. Kg2 Rxc6 $13 {as in Siedentopf-Dickhoff, Dresden 2003,}) ({or for} 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Nd7 16. Qd3 axb4 17. axb4 Ne5 $13 {Zaja-Jukic, Solin 1993,}) ({or, finally, for} 14. Qa4 axb4 15. axb4 {( 15.Qxc6? Bd7-+ )} Bd7 16. b5 Ne5 17. Qd4 Bxc5 18. Qxe5 Bxf2+ 19. Kf1 Ba7 20. Bf3 Qb6 21. Nd1 Bxb5 $13 {Lugovoi-Womacka, Hamburg 2001. Black should be happy with the opening outcome as he can have too early his equal share of potential success.}) 14... axb4 $1 {An excellent exchange sacrifice.} 15. Bxb8 bxc3 16. Qa4 $6 ({But this is too much. Good or bad White had to go for} 16. Bd6 Bxd6 17. cxd6 Ba6 {( 17...Qxd6 18.Rb3 e5 19.Rxc3 Bd7 20.O-O d4 $17 )} 18. Qa4 Bxe2 19. Qxc6 Bc4 $17 {.}) 16... Nxb8 17. Rxb8 Nd7 $1 18. Ra8 (18. Rb1 Nxc5 19. Qc2 {( 19.Qd4 c2-+ )} Ba6) ({Or} 18. Rb5 Nxc5 19. Qd4 Ba6 $1 20. Rxc5 Bxe2 21. Kxe2 Qb6 {.}) 18... Nxc5 19. Qb5 ({Or} 19. Qd4 Qb6 $1 20. Nxc3 Qb7 $1 21. Ra5 Nb3 22. Qa7 Qc6 23. O-O Qxc3 24. Rb5 Nd4 25. Rb8 Bxa3 26. Rfb1 Bd6 27. Ra8 Bc5 28. Qa1 Nf3+ 29. Bxf3 Qxf3 30. Qb2 e5 {0-1, Vidyakin-Antipin, Moscow 2007.}) 19... Qd6 $1 ({Also, good enough was} 19... d4) ({(And} 19... c2 $1 {)}) 20. O-O e5 {( 20...c2? 21.Rxc8 Qxc8 22.Nxd4= Nd3? 23.Nc6+- )} 21. Rc1 {Qd6-+ . Bf3} ({O-O Ba6} 21. Ra6 Nxa6 22. Qb3 c2 {.}) 21... Ba6 22. Rxf8+ Bxf8 23. Qa5 (23. Qb1 Nd3 24. Kf1 Qc5 {, mates!}) 23... Nd3 24. Kf1 {Ne5 Qxc3} {Kg2 Nxf3 Kxf3 d4-+ .} d4 {Qb3 Bc4} (24... Bc4 {White decided that he had enough and called it a day due to Qb7 Nxf3 Qxf3} 25. Bxd5 {.}) 0-1

