1. Z0 {In many openings (Caro-Kann Defense, Nimzo-Indian Defense, Sicilian Defense, French Defense, Queen's Pawn Opening, and others), a pawn formation of the type shown in the following diagram can arise StartFEN8/pp3ppp/4p3/8/8/8/PPP2PPP/8 w - - 0 1EndFEN The two sides' plans normally follow from the pawn formation: the four pawns advance against the three on the kingside, and the three against the two on the queenside, although cases of a minority attack are also possible. Formerly it was considered more favorable to have the extra pawn on the queenside since it is easier to set up a passed pawn there. The modern-day practice hasn’t confirmed this unshakable principle of the ‘Steinitz Theory’. Everything depends on the specific features of the position. In most cases, controlling the only open file confers an advantage, irrespective of the number of pawns on the wings. In general, this is a very difficult concept to work out, due to many and various possibilities.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 1: Pawn "]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.05.28"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.1) The Positive Central Maj"]
[Black "The Positive Central Majority"]
