1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Bxc4 Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. Ke2 Nf6 13. f3 {White is slightly better, as he possesses an extra pawn in the center (better central control), which significantly restricts the black pieces. Furthermore, his central pawn majority seems to be more mobile than the black queenside one.} Ke7 14. Rhd1 a5 $6 {This move weakens Black's position without gaining anything in return. We must always keep in mind that pawns don't move backwards and thus every pawn move must be carefully considered.} 15. Rac1 ({White could have won a tempo with the immediate} 15. Ke3 {.}) 15... Rxd1 16. Rxd1 Rb8 17. Ke3 g6 $1 (17... b5 $6 18. Bf1 {, intending Ne2-d4 and Rc1, would present White with more queenside weaknesses to target.}) 18. Bb3 Ra8 19. Rd4 {Black's greatest problem is his inability to coordinate and activate his pieces; thus, they are doomed to permanent defense. On the other hand, White centralizes his troops and prepares to develop play in the center and on the kingside, assisted by his pawn majority (4:3) on that side(s) of the board.} Nd7 20. Bd5 $1 Ra6 ({Naturally, the white bishop is a better piece than its black counterpart, but this specific exchange offer contains certain tactical nuances. As Black is unable to continue with} 20... Bxd5 $2 21. Nxd5+ Kd8 22. Nf6 {, he is compelled either to allow the doubling of his pawns on the c-file or to misplace his rook. It must be noted that 20...Ne5 21.h3! g5 22.g3 , intending 23.f4, would also not help Black.}) 21. f4 f6 22. h4 $1 h6 23. g3 $1 ({Black is ready to meet the advance} 23. g4 {, with} g5 $1 {but he has also created additional weaknesses on his kingside.}) 23... Bxd5 ({Black has no more useful moves:} 23... Nc5 24. Rc4 $16 {,}) ({or} 23... Nf8 24. Bc4 $1 Ra8 {24...Rb6 25.b3 $16} 25. h5 $1 gxh5 26. Nd5+ Bxd5 27. Rxd5 $16 {, with advantage for White.}) 24. Nxd5+ Kd8 25. Nc3 $1 {White will now exploit the bad placement of the black rook, while also trying for the h5 advance. Despite appearances, Black's position is very difficult.} Rb6 26. Rd2 $1 c6 27. h5 $1 g5 $2 ({Good or bad, Black had to try} 27... gxh5 $1 28. b3 $1 h4 $1 {28...Rb4?! 29.Rh2+-} 29. gxh4 Rb4 30. Rg2 $16 {.}) 28. Kf3 Ke7 29. Ne2 $6 (29. Nd1 $1 {, seems to be even stronger:} gxf4 30. gxf4 Rb5 31. Rh2 Ke6 32. Ne3 {.}) 29... c5 ({No better is} 29... gxf4 30. gxf4 Rb5 31. Ng3 $1 {(the idea of 29.Ne2!). Black tries to set his queenside majority in motion, but he only succeeds in creating further targets for his opponent.}) 30. Nc3 $1 {Unfortunately, every move by the black pawns creates new weaknesses and the white pieces seem always to be well placed to exploit them.} Rd6 31. Rd5 $1 {White doesn't hesitate to exchange rooks as well, evaluating the resulting knight endgame as won.} Rxd5 (31... Ke6 32. Kg4 $1 Rxd5 33. exd5+ Kf7 34. Ne4 {, is also losing for Black.}) 32. Nxd5+ Ke6 33. Ne3 b5 $6 ({Only very few saving chances were offered by} 33... Nb6 {.}) 34. Nf5 Nb6 35. Nxh6 Nc4 36. Nf5 Kf7 {Forced, due to the threat of h6-h7-h8Q!.} 37. b3 Nd2+ 38. Ke3 1-0

