1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 c6 3. c4 d5 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qe7 10. a3 Bc7 11. Ba2 e5 12. h3 h6 13. Bd2 a5 14. Nh4 Re8 15. Nf5 Qf8 16. dxe5 Rxe5 {In this asymmetrical pawn structure position, White seems to stand better due to his space advantage and better placed pieces. But there is more to come!} 17. f4 Re8 18. e4 $1 {White's superiority is indisputable and is mainly owed to his mobile central/kingside pawn majority. In sharp contrast, Black's queenside pawn majority cannot advance without creating weak squares and cannot become threatening. The qualitative difference of the white e4-pawn compared to Black's c6-pawn is immense and effectively determines the outcome of the game.} Nb6 19. e5 Nh5 $6 ({Black's position hardly inspires confidence, but in any case} 19... Bxf5 20. Qxf5 Rad8 21. Rad1 Nfd5 22. Kh2 $16) ({or} 19... Nfd5 20. Rad1 {20.Nxd5?! Nxd5 21.Bxd5 Bxf5 22.Qxf5 Qc5+ 23.Kh2 Qxd5 24.Bc3 $14} Qc5+ 21. Kh2 Bxf5 22. Qxf5 $16 {was necessary.}) 20. Nxh6+ $1 {White's great strategic plus creates the preconditions for successful combinations.} ({But also} 20. Nd4 $1 {seems to kill Black, as the threat of Qg6 is rather strong:} Qc5 21. Be3 Nd5 {21...Rd8 22.Rad1} 22. Bxd5 cxd5 23. Qf2 {.}) 20... gxh6 21. Qg6+ Ng7 22. Ne4 $1 Qe7 $6 ({White wins after} 22... Nd7 23. Bc3 $1 {and Nf6+, as well, but Black}) ({had to play} 22... Bd8 $1 {, were White would be 'obliged' to find some strong moves:} 23. Nf6+ {23.Qxh6? Nd5 24.Bxd5 cxd5 25.Nf6+ Bxf6 26.exf6 Nf5 27.Qg5+ Kh7 28.Rae1 Rxe1 28...Be6? 29.g4 Qh6 30.gxf5! Rg8 31.Kh2 Rxg5 32.fxg5 Qf8 33.g6++- 29.Qh5+ Nh6 30.Rxe1 Ra6 31.Qg5 Re6 32.Re5= $13} Bxf6 24. exf6 Be6 25. Qxh6 $1 {25.Bxe6?! Rxe6 26.Qxg7+ Qxg7 27.fxg7 $14} Nf5 {25...Bxa2 26.Rf3! Nd7 27.Rg3 Nxf6 28.Bc3+-} 26. Qg5+ Kh8 27. Bb1 $1 Nc4 28. Bxf5 Bxf5 29. Qxf5 Nxd2 30. Qh5+ Kg8 31. Rac1 {. Black now loses simply, as his pieces are suffocating.}) 23. Nf6+ Kf8 24. Nh7+ Kg8 25. Nf6+ Kf8 26. Qxh6 Qc5+ 27. Kh1 {Black resigned as he loses too much material.} 1-0

