1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. Ne5 Nbd7 7. Nxc4 Qc7 8. g3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 Nfd7 11. Bg2 Rd8 12. Qc1 f6 13. O-O Be6 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Ne4 Qa5 16. Bd2 Bb4 17. Bxb4 Qxb4 18. Qf4 Qe7 19. Qe3 a6 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. b4 Nf7 22. Ra3 Nd6 23. Rd1 Qxe3 24. Rxe3+ Kf7 25. Red3 Ke7 26. Re3+ Kf7 27. Red3 Ke7 {After White's idea a4 (and a5), Black's queenside pawns will be paralysed. The open d-file is in White's possession and his minor pieces are better placed than his opponent's.} 28. f4 $6 {It is time to set about realising the kingside pawn majority. At the same time a way for the king to the centre is opened.} ({But accurate was} 28. a5 Nc4 29. Bf1 $1 Rxd3 30. Rxd3 Rd8 31. Rxd8 Kxd8 32. e4 $16 {.}) 28... Nc4 29. Kf2 Rxd3 30. Rxd3 Rd8 31. Rxd8 Kxd8 {With the exchange of rooks, the position has simplified and White's advantage has become obvious.} 32. Be4 $1 {The knight has to be driven from its strong position at c4. To this aim the bishop is transferred to d3, at the same time provoking a fresh weakening of his opponent's kingside.} h6 $2 ({Although} 32... f5 $1 {doesn't look attractive, it was forced:} 33. Bd3 Nb2 34. a5 Kc7 35. Ke3 b6 36. Nb3 Nxd3 37. Kxd3 Be6 38. Nd4 Bd7 $14 {.}) 33. Bd3 $6 {White is not playing with accuracy.} ({Good was} 33. a5 Kc7 34. Na4 $16 {.}) 33... Nb6 $2 ({After} 33... Nb2 $1 {, Black can achieve counterplay:} 34. a5 Kc7 35. Ke3 b6 36. Ne4 $14 {.}) 34. e4 {Black has no way of opposing the advance of the white pawn majority in the centre.} Na8 35. Ke3 Nc7 36. a5 $1 {36...b6 was threatened.} Ke7 37. Bc4 Kd6 38. Kd4 Ne8 39. e5+ {The central majority is transformed to a strong passed pawn.} fxe5+ 40. fxe5+ Ke7 41. h4 $1 {Good technique. According to the rules of the endgame the king and knight should have changed places. But G.Levenfish puts his opponent in zugzwang, forcing him to weaken d6 for the decisive invasion by the white knight.} (41. Nb3 Nc7 42. Kc5 {was also rather strong.}) 41... Nc7 (41... g5 {fails to} 42. hxg5 hxg5 43. Ne4 g4 {- the white king goes across to f4 and wins the pawn.}) 42. Ne4 Be6 43. Nd6 Bxc4 {Otherwise, the white king breaks through at b6.} 44. Kxc4 Ke6 45. Nxb7 Z0 ({Black resigned in view of the obvious} 45... Kxe5 46. Kc5 Nd5 47. Nd8 Ke4 48. Nxc6 Nc3 49. Nb8 Kf3 50. Nxa6 Kxg3 51. Nc7 {.}) 1-0

