{26.Rxf5 Bc8 Bxe4 27.Na1 27.Nd4 Rd6 , or 27.Na3 Rxd1 28.Rxd1 Re6 29.Rd8+ Kf7 30.Bc1 Bxa3 Rxd1 28.Rxd1 Bf3 29.Rd2 29.Rd7 Bg4+ 30.Kh4 Be7+ Bg4+ 30.Kg2 Re1 31.h3 Rg1+ 32.Kh2 Bf3 33.g4 f4! .} 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 4. e3 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. b3 Qe7 10. Bb2 b6 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Bb7 14. Bd3 $6 f5 $1 ({A pointless move, hoping for} 14... Nf6 $6 15. Qh4 h6 16. Rfe1 {, with a slight edge for White. He should instead have preferred 14.Qe3 c5 15.Rfd1 Rad8 16.dxc5 , with equality.}) {An excellent idea, aiming to create a mobile pawn majority on the centre/kingside. Black will exchange his c-pawn with White's d-pawn and obtain a 4:3 majority on the centre/kingside, which will be able to advance menacingly. On the contrary, White's 3:2 queenside majority will remain immobile for several moves or, even worse, will never succeed in becoming threatening.} 15. Qe2 c5 16. Rad1 $6 {White fails to comprehend the problems of the position.} ({He should have played} 16. h3) ({or} 16. d5 $6 exd5 17. Qxe7 Rxe7 18. Bxf5 d4 $17 {instead, and try to defend.}) 16... cxd4 17. Nxd4 Qh4 $1 ({Better than} 17... Nc5 $6 18. Nb5 Bb8 19. Be5 $1 {19.Bb1 a6 20.Nc3 Bc7 $15} Nxd3 20. Bxb8 Raxb8 21. Rxd3 Be4 22. Rd2 Red8 $13 {.}) 18. g3 Qh3 ({18...Ne5?! 19.Nb5! Nf3+ 20.gxf3 Qxh3 21.Nxd6 Bxf3 22.Qxf3 Qxf3 23.Nxe8 Rxe8 23...Qg4+= 24.Rfe1 $13 g3} 18... Qh6 19. h4 Ne5 {, leaves Black with a decisive superiority (as} 20. Bxf5 $2 {, fails to} exf5 21. Nxf5 Qg6 {).}) 19. f3 ({Optically displeasing, but the alternative} 19. Nf3 Ne5 $5 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 {was not helpful.}) 19... Bc5 20. Kh1 Nf6 {Black's superiority is obvious, as he has some dangerous plans at his disposal (advance of the pawn majority, attack against the white king) while White cannot react effectively.} 21. Nc2 $6 {Allowing the immediate advance of the black pawns.} ({White should struggle on with} 21. Qg2 Qh5 22. Bb1 {,}) ({or} 21. Nb5 $5 Re7 22. Bd4 {instead.}) 21... e5 $1 22. Qg2 Qxg2+ 23. Kxg2 e4 24. fxe4 ({Compulsory, as} 24. Be2 {loses immediately to} exf3+ 25. Bxf3 Re2+ $1 {.}) 24... Nxe4 25. Kh3 Rad8 $1 ({A 'quiet' move, to which White has no good reply. It must be noted that Black could win an exchange with} 25... Nf2+ 26. Rxf2 Bxf2 27. Bxf5 {, but his position is so good that he seeks to extract even greater gains!}) 26. Z0 0-1

