1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Be6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bg5 Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Ne5 Nxd4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. e3 Nf3+ 14. Nxf3 exf3 15. Qxf3 O-O {The starting position is not (still) an endgame one, but play soon goes into an ending where Black seizes control of the d-file, which in fact decides the outcome.} 16. Rfc1 $6 ({White should have begun a battle for the d-file and advanced his kingside pawns, So, best is} 16. Rfd1 {, with a roughly equal game.}) ({Note that} 16. Qxb7 Qxb7 17. Bxb7 Rab8 18. Bf3 Rxb2 $15 {, can only favour Black.}) 16... Rab8 17. Qe4 {With the threat of exchanging bishops after Bh3. Again, White deviates from the correct path...} Qc7 $1 {A simple move, yet at the same time difficult to find. It is not so easy voluntarily to place the queen opposite an enemy rook. But this move is part of a plan to provoke White into opening-up the game on the queenside, which could only favour Black and his mobile majority.} 18. Rc3 $6 ({Of course, it is difficult to admit one's mistake. At the given moment there would not have been anything particularly terrible in store for White after the correct} 18. Rd1 {. But after the move played his position begins to deteriorate, the reason being that Black seizes control of the d-file.}) 18... b5 $1 19. a3 $6 ({The text only helps Black to expand on the queenside.} 19. b3 {, should be a better pawn formation for White.}) 19... c4 20. Bf3 Rfd8 21. Rd1 Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 Rd8 {Black has got a good mobile queenside pawn majority and the advantage. 'Black now dominates the entire board - E.Lasker'.} 23. Bf3 {Here, 100 years later, the game Guerra Hernandez,C-Perez Torres,Y Havana 2009, ended in a draw...} g6 $1 ({Black carefully avoids any back-rank tricks. Not much is gained by} 23... Rd2 $2 24. Bg4 $1 {( 24.Rc2 Rd8 ( 24...Bd5? 25.Qe8 ) 25.Qb7 Qxb7 26.Bxb7 $15 )} Qd6 25. Bxe6 fxe6 26. Qa8+ Qd8 27. Qxd8+ Rxd8 28. b3 {.}) 24. Qc6 Qe5 $1 {J.R.Capablanca doesn't object to an endgame, but only in a different version...} 25. Qe4 Qxe4 26. Bxe4 Rd1+ $1 {The white king must be decentralised.} 27. Kg2 a5 {The black pawn majority is ruling!} 28. Rc2 b4 29. axb4 axb4 30. Bf3 Rb1 31. Be2 b3 $1 32. Rd2 (32. Rc3 $6 Rxb2 33. Bxc4 Rc2 {, ends the game.}) 32... Rc1 $1 {Now the coming ...Rc2, would be lethal.} 33. Bd1 c3 34. bxc3 b2 $1 {Black wins a piece, and the realisation of his advantage doesn't present any great difficulty.} 35. Rxb2 (35. Bc2 {, loses to} Rxc2 {.}) 35... Rxd1 36. Rc2 Bf5 37. Rb2 Rc1 38. Rb3 Be4+ 39. Kh3 Rc2 40. f4 h5 41. g4 hxg4+ 42. Kxg4 Rxh2 43. Rb4 f5+ 44. Kg3 (44. Kg5 $6 Kg7 {, leads to mate.}) 44... Re2 45. Rc4 Rxe3+ 46. Kh4 Kg7 47. Rc7+ Kf6 48. Rd7 Bg2 $1 49. Rd6+ Kg7 {White resigned, as the coming ...Kh6 and ...Rh3+, or ...Rh3-h5+, mates the white king.} 0-1

