1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Rc1 c6 8. h3 a6 9. a3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 b5 11. Ba2 Bb7 12. O-O c5 13. d5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Qxd5 Nf6 17. Qb7 Re8 18. Rfd1 Qc8 19. Qxc8 Raxc8 20. Bd6 Kf8 21. Kf1 Ne4 22. Bxe7+ Kxe7 23. Rd5 {Black's position is preferable: his queenside pawns have advanced, whereas White's on the kingside are not yet ready to move. The centralised black king has greater scope than White's. But White controls the important d-file. With his next move B.Spassky begins a battle for the only open file.} Rcd8 24. Rh5 $6 ({B.Larsen plans to attack with his pawn minority. After} 24. Rcd1 {, the position would have been approximately level.}) 24... h6 25. b4 c4 26. a4 ({It was this position that B.Larsen was aiming for. But, he should have exchanged one pair of rooks by} 26. Re5+ {and blocked the d-file by Nd4.}) 26... Kf6 $1 27. axb5 g6 $1 {A brilliant manoeuvre. Black sacrifices a kingside pawn, shutting the white rook out of play for a long time. He will then attack on the queenside with superior forces.} 28. Rxh6 axb5 29. Nd4 $2 ({This loses. After} 29. Rh4 Rd3 30. Rf4+ Kg7 31. Nd4 Nd2+ 32. Ke2 Nb3 33. Rd1 Nxd4+ 34. Rxd4 Rb3 {, Black would have obtained two connected passed pawns, but the outcome of the game would still have been unclear.}) 29... Nd2+ 30. Kg1 {The king cannot stand on the e-file due to 30...Rxd4.} Nb3 $1 31. Nxb3 cxb3 32. Rb1 (32. Rh4 {, is too late due to} b2 33. Rb1 Rd2 34. Rd4 Rxd4 35. exd4 Re2 {.}) 32... Re4 $1 {Black again exploits the unfortunate position of the rook at h6.} 33. g3 (33. Rxb3 $2 Kg7 {, is the point!}) 33... Rxb4 34. Rh4 {The rook has finally broken free, but it is too late.} Rxh4 35. gxh4 Rd3 36. Kg2 Ke5 {White resigned, as the black king's penetration by ...Kd5-c4-c3, would be decisive.} 0-1

