1. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. O-O c5 8. e4 Nf6 9. e5 Nd5 10. dxc5 Nb4 11. Nc3 N8c6 12. Qe2 Qd3 13. Rd1 Qxe2 14. Nxe2 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Rd2 Nc6 18. Nf4 Bf5 19. Re1 Bg7 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 {White's queenside pawns have gained space, and all his pieces are ready to support their advance. In addition, the d-file is under White's control.} 21. a3 g5 $6 ({Black fails to battle for the only open file, and ends up in a very difficult position. 'Black doesn't yet sense the danger and chooses an ineffective method of defence. He should have tried} 21... Rad8 {, so as after} 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Rxe7 g5 $13 {, to gain counterplay at the cost of a pawn - V.Smyslov'.}) 22. Nd5 Red8 23. Red1 Bg4 24. f3 Be6 25. b4 $1 ({White advances his pawns further, avoiding the positional trap} 25. Nc7 $6 Bb3 $1 {.}) 25... h6 26. Kf2 Rd7 27. Nc3 $1 ({Black resourcefully exploits White's last move (now} 27. Nf4 {, is not possible, since the rook takes on d2 with check) and successfully contests the d-file, but it is too late.}) 27... Rxd2+ 28. Rxd2 Rd8 29. Rxd8 Nxd8 {Black reduced material and nullified the control of the d-file by exchanging all rooks, but still his position looks rather difficult, due to White's mobile queenside pawn majority.} 30. f4 $1 gxf4 31. gxf4 Bb3 {In order to stop the white pawns, Black tries to bring his king across and vacates e6 for it, but he runs into another misfortune.} 32. Ke3 Kf6 33. b5 e5 ({The intended} 33... Ke6 {, would not have worked, since, as shown by V.Smyslov, White then has a pretty win:} 34. c6 bxc6 35. bxc6 Kd6 36. Nb5+ {.}) 34. Ne4+ Ke6 35. c6 $1 {Exploiting the tactical features of the position.} exf4+ 36. Kxf4 bxc6 {There is nothing else to do...} 37. Nc5+ Kd6 38. Nxb3 {White has won a piece, and the rest is not difficult.} cxb5 39. h4 Nc6 40. Bxc6 Kxc6 41. Kg4 b4 42. axb4 Kb5 43. Nd4+ 1-0

