{Considering D. Bronstein's decision to advance kingside pawns instead of doubling rooks on the d-file, what would be the next strategic move for White to effectively utilize the kingside pawn advance? How can White leverage this advancement to gain control of the critical d-file invasion squares and create a favorable scenario for a queenside pawn advance, capitalizing on their numerical superiority in that area?} 20. g4 $1 {[%mdl 32768]} a6 21. g5 ({Better than} 21. a4 Ra7 22. Be3 Rb7 23. Ne2 Nd7 {Motuz, K-Likavsky, T Slovakia 2016.}) 21... Ne8 {White has chosen a very favourable moment for the advance of his g-pawn. Black's kingside is now paralysed, and for the moment his extra pawn on this part of the board is of no significance at all.} 22. a4 $1 ({The black counterplay by ...b5, should be kept in bay:} 22. h4 Kf8 23. Rd3 Rc5 24. Nc2 b5 {Andersson, U-Tatai, S Rome 1985.}) *

