1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 8. Bf4 b6 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qe2 c5 14. Rad1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Qc8 16. b3 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qb7+ 18. Qf3 Qxf3+ 19. Kxf3 Rfc8 {The doubling of rooks on the d-file suggests itself, but D.Bronstein, after a subtle evaluation of the position, begins advancing his kingside pawns. White's idea is not to carry out a minority attack, but to push back the opponent's firmly established pieces on the kingside and gain control of the invasion squares on the d-file, thereby creating the preconditions for a pawn advance on the queenside, where White has a quantitative majority.} 20. g4 $1 a6 21. g5 ({Better than} 21. a4 Ra7 22. Be3 Rb7 23. Ne2 Nd7 {Motuz, K-Likavsky,T Slovakia 2016.}) 21... Ne8 {White has chosen a very favourable moment for the advance of his g-pawn. Black's kingside is now paralysed, and for the moment his extra pawn on this part of the board is of no significance at all.} 22. a4 $1 ({The black counterplay by ...b5, should be kept in bay:} 22. h4 Kf8 23. Rd3 Rc5 24. Nc2 b5 {Andersson,U-Tatai,S Rome 1985.}) 22... Ra7 23. h4 $1 {In order to free his bishop from having to defend the g5-pawn.} Rb7 ({Black persists in his desire to obtain counterplay on the queenside, where he is clearly weaker. He should have gone totally onto the defensive. To be considered was} 23... Kf8 {, transferring the king to e7 after ...Bc5, and thus covering White's invasion squares on the d-file.}) 24. Rd3 {White sets about doubling rooks on the d-file.} Rc5 {With the threat of 25...e5.} 25. Re1 $1 Rd7 $6 {Black wrongly thought that he has set a threat; the text allows White, by using tactical motifs, to seize full control of the d-file.} 26. Red1 $1 g6 ({Unfortunately for Black, the planned} 26... e5 $2 {, doesn’t work:} 27. Nf5 Rxd3+ 28. Rxd3 Kf8 {, then ( 28...exf4 29.Nxe7+ Kf8 30.Nd5+- )} 29. Be3 {, with an overwhelming positional advantage.}) 27. Ne2 $1 {The d-file is completely in White's hands.} Rxd3+ 28. Rxd3 b5 $6 ({This merely accelerates Black's inevitable defeat. But Black had hardly any good move left:} 28... Ng7 29. Be3 Rc6 30. Rd7 Kf8 31. Ra7 a5 32. Ra8+ Ne8 33. Nd4 {.}) 29. cxb5 axb5 30. Rd7 $1 Kf8 31. a5 Rc6 32. Rb7 b4 33. Rb8 Bc5 34. Ng3 $1 {After 35.Ne4, loss of material is inevitable, and so Black resigned.} 1-0

