1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. e4 d6 6. h3 Na6 7. Bg5 e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8 Rxd8 10. Nd5 Rd6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Rc1 Bd8 13. c5 Re6 14. a3 c6 15. Bxa6 cxd5 16. Bd3 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Re7 18. O-O f5 19. Rfd1 Bc7 20. Bd5+ Kg7 {The pawn structures determines the two sides' play. White is obliged to play on the queenside and the d-file, while Black must seek his chances in the centre and on the kingside. Black's possession of the bishop pair is counterbalanced by the ability of the white pieces to occupy better posts, mainly on the squares of the d-file.} 21. Nd2 $1 {The white knight heads for the outpost on d6 and White can claim a small edge.} Rb8 22. Nc4 Kf6 23. Rd2 e4 ({The psychological necessity of advancing his majority is understandable, but it was more important for Black to focus on defence with} 23... Bd7 $1) ({(} 23... Be6 $6 24. Bxe6 Kxe6 25. Rcd1 {)}) 24. b4 {Bc6! , with only a slight -but very pleasant- advantage for White. Rcd1} Bf4 25. Rd4 Be6 $6 ({A mistaken exchange. Black should opt for the other bishop exchange by} 25... Be5 $1 26. Nxe5 Kxe5 $14 {, which offers him better chances to hold the position. Well, it wasn’t an easy decision to make…}) 26. Bxe6 Kxe6 {b4 White's superiority is pleasant, as he possesses three significant advantages: the 3:2 mobile pawn majority on the queenside, he controls the only open d-file and his c4-knight is a much stronger piece than the f4-bishop. Bc7} 27. Kf1 {The last remaining white piece enters the battle! The white king will play an important role, creating further weaknesses in Black’s camp and attack them as well! Black is forced to passively observe events as they unfold and actually this is his main disadvantage…} Kf7 $2 ({This passive approach cannot be recommended. Black had to opt for} 27... b6 $1 28. Rd5 bxc5 29. Rxc5 Rd7 {Rxd7 Kxd7} 30. g4 $14 {.}) 28. a4 a6 29. Ke2 Rf8 30. Nd6+ $1 {A ‘strange’ exchange at first sight. White surrenders one of his advantages but can now more easily invade Black's camp. His assessment is proved correct.} Bxd6 31. Rxd6 Rc8 32. a5 $1 {An apparently 'illogical' move, seemingly ruining White's queenside majority. White judged that it is more important to prevent any counterplay with 33...a5, while he will later be able to destroy the black pawn chain with the c6 advance.} Rcc7 33. Ke3 Kg7 34. g4 $1 {This effectively is a minority attack. White aims to weaken the black kingside pawn chain, so as to make it more vulnerable to the attack from the white king and rooks.} fxg4 ({Forced, as he loses quickly after} 34... Kf7 $2 35. gxf5 gxf5 {R1d5+- . However, the text is hardly desirable either.}) 35. hxg4 Rf7 36. g5 $6 {Clearer was R1d4 Kh6 ( 37...Rf3+ 38.Kxe4+- ) Rxe4+- .} Rce7 {R1d4?} ({An accurate win could be found in Ke2! Rc7 ( 38...Rf4 39.Rd7+- ) R1d4} 36... Rce7 37. c6 bxc6 {Rxc6+- .}) {Rf3+} 37. Ke2 {Rff7? Ke3?} {Returning the favour. After Ref7! Rxe4 Rxf2+ Kd3 h6! gxh6+ Kxh6 , it seems that Black could save the draw.} Rf3 {Ke2 Rff7? After some repeated mistakes in time-trouble, White finds the correct way to exploit Black's weaknesses.} 38. c6 $1 {White has succeeded in fixing the black pawns (a6, e4 and h7) and turning them into targets. The final stage now commences, i.e., the transformation of the positional superiority into a material one. Black tried to defend actively, but his position proved too weak for this.} bxc6 {Rxc6 Rf5 Rxa6 Rxg5 Rad6! It is important to exchange a pair of rooks, as then the white duo on the queenside will advance without troubles. Rb5 a6 Kh6} 39. Rd5 {Rb6 b5} Rc7 {Ra4! Ra7 Rc5 Kg7 Rac4 Kh6 Rxe4} 40. Rd7+ {Ra4 Ra7 Ra5 And as coming Rc6 breaks Black's blockade, he resigned.} 1-0

