33. a5 $1 {[%mdl 32768] In (nearly) all the games examined by now, control of the d-file was a decisive factor. It is true that one comes across endings (usually with just one pair of rooks) where this doesn't give any real advantage, but these are merely exceptions which confirm the rule. In conclusion we will examine an example in which the side with the initiative achieves success by play on the wing where the opponent has a pawn majority. Here, with rooks on the board, he has a bishop against a knight, which is in itself an advantage when there is play on both wings. An experienced player will immediately be aware that the position has arisen from a 'Caro-Kann Defence'. Black controls the d-file, but this is of no significance, since there are not, and cannot be, any invasion squares on it. On the other hand, Black's pawn structure on the kingside, where he has a numerical superiority, is completely fixed by the three white pawns, and the difference in strength between the white bishop and black knight is so great that the position can be assessed as won for White. In light of this comment, how should White proceed? In the plan of creating a passed pawn on the queenside, this move seems illogical. But G. Kasparov makes a concrete assessment of the position, and finds a plan based on exploiting the difference in strength of the bishop and knight. This aim is best served by a minority attack with f4 and g5. At the same time, he suppresses Black's only chance of counterplay - the attempt to create a strong point for his knight at d5. Black was planning to carry out the counterblow ... b5 at a convenient moment, and to set up the defensive formation ...Ne8, ...f6 and ...Nc7. G.Kasparov radically forestalls Black's plan of removing the c4-pawn's control of d5.} Ne8 34. Re1 $1 {White again denies his opponent counterplay. It is not at all in his interests to allow ...f6.} *

