1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Qc7 12. O-O-O Ngf6 13. Ne4 O-O-O 14. g3 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Be7 16. Kb1 Rhe8 17. Qe2 Bd6 18. Rhe1 Re7 19. c4 c5 20. Bc3 Nf6 21. Ne5 cxd4 22. Rxd4 Bxe5 23. Rxd8+ Qxd8 24. Bxe5 Rd7 25. Bc3 Qb6 26. g4 Qd6 27. f3 a6 28. a4 Qd3+ 29. Kc1 Kc7 30. Qxd3 Rxd3 31. Rf1 Kc6 32. Kc2 Rd7 {In (nearly) all the games examined by now, control of the d-file was a decisive factor. It is true that one comes across endings (usually with just one pair of rooks) where this doesn't give any real advantage, but these are merely exceptions which confirm the rule. In conclusion we will examine an example in which the side with the initiative achieves success by play on the wing where the opponent has a pawn majority. Here, with rooks on the board, he has a bishop against a knight, which is in itself an advantage when there is play on both wings. An experienced player will immediately be aware that the position has arisen from a 'Caro-Kann Defence'. Black controls the d-file, but this is of no significance, since there are not, and cannot be, any invasion squares on it. On the other hand, Black's pawn structure on the kingside, where he has a numerical superiority, is completely fixed by the three white pawns, and the difference in strength between the white bishop and black knight is so great that the position can be assessed as won for White.} 33. a5 $1 {In the plan of creating a passed pawn on the queenside, this move seems illogical. But G.Kasparov makes a concrete assessment of the position, and finds a plan based on exploiting the difference in strength of the bishop and knight. This aim is best served by a minority attack with f4 and g5. At the same time, he suppresses Black's only chance of counterplay - the attempt to create a strong point for his knight at d5. Black was planning to carry out the counterblow ...b5 at a convenient moment, and to set up the defensive formation ...Ne8, ...f6 and ...Nc7. G.Kasparov radically forestalls Black's plan of removing the c4-pawn's control of d5.} Ne8 34. Re1 $1 {White again denies his opponent counterplay. It is not at all in his interests to allow ...f6.} Rd6 35. f4 Nf6 $6 {The decisive mistake in a difficult position. Now White takes play into a pawn ending. But it must be noted that there was no salvation for Black:} (35... Kd7 36. g5 f6 {( 36...Rc6 37.Rd1+ Kc8 38.Bxg7+- )} 37. b3 fxg5 38. fxg5 hxg5 39. Rg1) ({Or} 35... f6 36. Bb4 Rd4 37. Rxe6+ Kd7 38. Re7+ Kd8 39. Kb3 {.}) 36. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 37. Rd1 $1 (37. Rd1 {After the exchange of rooks Black has no satisfactory defence against g5:} Rxd1 38. Kxd1 Kc5 39. g5 fxg5 40. fxg5 hxg5 41. h6 {.}) 1-0

