1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Ne7 9. Bd3 b6 10. Nf3 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nd7 {Black seems to have successfully played the opening, as White can hardly claim any advantage. He is ready to castle and he can then decide to play with hanging pawns (by ...c5) or to stay put, waiting for white activities to play against them.} 13. e4 $1 O-O ({White's point is that after} 13... dxe4 $2 14. Nxe4 Qd5 {( 14...Qe6 15.Qa3! O-O ? 16.Nfg5+- )} 15. Qa3 $1 {, Black will not be able to castle! Therefore, he will have to let the e4-pawn move forward.}) 14. e5 {White now has an edge due to his space advantage and he will focus on the kingside, as there lies his pawn majority.} Qe6 15. Rae1 $1 Rfe8 ({Maybe Black could have considered} 15... f6 $5 {, but it is very difficult and in most cases inadvisable to play on the opponent's 'territory'.}) 16. Nh4 $1 {Revealing his 15th move; the rook should have stayed on f1 in order to help the advance of the f-pawn.} Ng6 (16... f5 $5 17. f4 {is interesting, as it would take White a lot of time to prepare the g4 advance, but nevertheless he would stand clearly better.}) 17. Nxg6 Qxg6 ({Or} 17... hxg6 18. f4 Qf5 {( 18...Rad8 19.Qf3 Qe7 20.g4 $16 )} 19. Qf3 $16 {.}) 18. Qd2 (18. Qxg6 $6 hxg6 19. f4 Nf8 {wouldn't be so bad for Black. White is obliged to keep pieces on the board, in order to better control his space advantage.}) 18... Nf8 (18... f5 {is not that effective now:} 19. Re3 Nf8 20. Ne2 Ne6 21. Rc3 Rac8 22. Rfc1 $16 {.}) 19. f4 Qf5 $6 (19... f5 {seems forced at this point, although White would still be on top:} 20. Rc1 Ne6 21. Nd1 Rac8 22. Ne3 Qf7 23. Qd3 Rf8 24. b4 $16 {. Instead, Black blocks White's f-pawn with his queen, which proves ineffective.}) 20. Nd1 $1 {It's all about the f5-square!} f6 21. Ne3 Qd7 22. Qd3 fxe5 {Black finds a way to parry White's threats but now the latter obtains a crushing pawn avalanche.} 23. dxe5 $1 (23. fxe5 Ne6 24. Nf5 $16 {also seems fine, but by the text move, White's majority will roll with the maximum effect.}) 23... Ne6 24. f5 Nc5 25. Qd4 Ne4 ({Desperation, rather than a blunder, as the other options are not helpful either:} 25... Kh8 26. e6 Qb7 {( 26...Qe7 27.b4 Ne4 28.b5+- )} 27. b4 Ne4 28. b5) ({Or} 25... a5 26. f6 {. White now wins a pawn and then converts his material advantage.}) 26. Nxd5 $1 Qxd5 ({Or} 26... cxd5 27. Rxe4 {.}) 27. Qxe4 Rad8 28. e6 (28. f6 $5 gxf6 29. Qg4+ Kh8 30. exf6 {wins as well.}) 28... Qxe4 29. Rxe4 Rd6 ({If} 29... Rd2 {, then} 30. b4 $1 {( 30.g4?! Rxb2 31.g5 Rb5 32.h4 Kf8 33.f6 Rd5 , is not clear).} Rxa2 31. Rc1 Rc8 32. Rec4 {.}) 30. g4 $1 {Of course! The pawn phalanx must roll!} Kf8 31. g5 Ke7 32. Kg2 (32. f6+ Kf8 33. Rfe1 {wins as well.}) 32... Rd5 33. Kg3 Kd6 34. h4 c5 35. f6 $1 {Time to finish the job!} gxf6 36. gxf6 Rd3+ 37. Kh2 Rd2+ 38. Kh1 {Black is helpless to the threat e7 and f7, so he threw the towel in!} 1-0

