1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2 Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 d6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bd7 8. O-O Be7 9. Ndb5 Qb8 10. a4 O-O 11. Bg5 a6 12. Na3 Qc7 13. Qe2 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Na5 15. Rd3 h6 16. Be3 e5 17. Rd2 Be6 18. f3 Nc4 19. Nxc4 Bxc4 20. Qd1 Rfd8 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. exd5 {The respective pawn structures have radically clarified. Both sides have obtained a 4:3 majority - White on the queenside and Black on the kingside. The two sides' plans must be adapted to comply with the situation.} Rf8 $1 {A logical regrouping of the black pieces, fully in line with the requirements of the position. The black pieces will be transferred to the kingside where, in conjunction with the ...f5 advance, they will seek to grab the initiative and eventually prove that it is more dangerous than White's on the queenside.} 23. Bh3 Rce8 24. a5 Bd8 25. Qf1 $1 {A strong move, allowing the white queenside pawn mass to advance (b4, c4).} Nh7 26. c4 f5 27. b4 f4 $2 {An optimistic continuation.} ({Black should have opted for} 27... Qf7 28. Ra3 h5 $13 {.}) 28. gxf4 $1 {Practically forced, as in any other case Black's attack would be strong (...e4, ...Ng5).} exf4 29. Bb6 Qe7 30. Be6+ Kh8 31. Bd4 $1 ({White rightly avoids} 31. Bxd8 $2 Qxd8 32. Re1 Ng5 33. Rde2 {, with chances for both sides in a complicated position.}) 31... Ng5 32. Rg2 $6 (32. Re1 Qc7 33. Qd3 Bf6 34. Bb6 $16 {was better.}) 32... Qc7 $1 ({And not the naive} 32... Nxe6 $2 33. dxe6 {, when White wins.}) 33. Re1 Bf6 $1 {Black has developed a more troublesome initiative and thus is calling the shots. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops would favour him, as then White would no longer possess the bishop pair.} 34. Bb6 Qb8 $6 ({It looked like} 34... Qe7 {was perfect, but White can sacrifice the exchange and obtain the much preferable game:} 35. Rxg5 $1 Bxg5 36. Kh1 $16 {.}) 35. Rg4 $2 ({Better was} 35. Bg4 $1 Rxe1 36. Qxe1 Be5 37. c5 $16 {.}) 35... Nxe6 36. Rxe6 Rxe6 37. dxe6 Qc8 $1 ({White would have taken hold of the initiative after the careless} 37... Be5 $2 38. e7 Re8 39. Bd8 $14 {.}) 38. Rxf4 Qxe6 {Now Black has good chances, due to the weakened white king.} 39. Qf2 Rc8 ({In time pressure Black failed to proceed with} 39... d5 $1 40. cxd5 Qxd5 {, when the weakness of the white king, along with Black's better placed pieces, would give him some advantage.}) 40. Re4 Qf5 41. Qg3 d5 $1 ({Only equality results from} 41... Rxc4 $2 42. Rxc4 Qb1+ 43. Kg2 Qa2+ 44. Bf2 Qxc4 45. Qxd6 {.}) 42. cxd5 Qxd5 43. Qg6 Rf8 $1 {A difficult move, as it abandons control of the open c-file, but the white king is the real target.} ({After} 43... Be5 44. Bf2 $1 Rc1+ 45. Kg2 Qb5 46. Be1 $1 {46.Re1?! Rxe1 47.Bxe1 Qe2+ 48.Bf2 Bd4 49.Qg3 Kh7 $15} Rc2+ 47. Bf2 {, White can hold the position.}) 44. Bc5 $2 {This 'easy' move is White's main mistake.} ({He should instead have played} 44. Bf2 $1 {, when after} Qd1+ 45. Kg2 Bh4 46. Qg4 Bxf2 47. Kxf2 Rd8 48. Re2 {, he could defend.}) 44... Qd1+ 45. Kg2 Bd4 $1 46. Qg3 ({Best, as other moves would lose immediately:} 46. Bxf8 $2 Qg1+ {,}) ({or} 46. Bxd4 $2 Qxf3+ 47. Kg1 Qf1# {.}) 46... Qg1+ 47. Kh3 Bxc5 48. bxc5 Qf1+ $1 (48... Qxc5 {is also winning, but Black correctly demands even more from his position.}) 49. Kg4 Rf6 50. Re1 $1 Qd3 $1 ({Not, of course,} 50... Rg6+ $2 51. Kh5 $1 Rxg3 52. Rxf1 Rg5+ 53. Kh4 Rxc5 54. Rb1 Rb5 55. Ra1 Kh7 $17 {.}) 51. Qf2 Qf5+ 52. Kh4 Qf4+ 53. Kh3 Qxf3+ 54. Qxf3 Rxf3+ 55. Kg4 Rc3 56. Re5 Ra3 57. Kf5 $1 Kh7 $1 ({All would be lost after} 57... Rxa5 $2 58. Kg6 {. But now Black's victory is certain, as a second pawn falls.}) 58. c6 bxc6 59. Rc5 Rh3 60. Kg4 Rxh2 61. Rxc6 Rg2+ 0-1

