1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. e3 c5 3. c4 d4 4. exd4 cxd4 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 Nf6 9. d3 O-O 10. a3 a5 11. Ne5 {An interesting new idea. In this pawn structure (reversed 'Benoni Defence'), each side will try to mobilise their pawn majority; White on the queenside (due to his c-pawn) by b4, and Black in the centre (due to the e-pawn) by ...e4. As a result, both sides will try not only to generate a dangerous initiative but also a passed pawn if possible.} Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Nd7 13. Rb5 $1 {As the queenside will be White's operations territory, all forces are focused in that direction.} Qc7 (13... Ra7 {is an alternative option:} 14. b4 axb4 15. Nd2 Ne5 $13 {Ivanov-Nabaty, Belgrade 2015.}) 14. Nd2 h6 (14... Nc5 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 $14 {is helping White, as then it becomes more difficult for Black to achieve the ...e4 advance.}) 15. Rb1 Ra7 $1 (15... a4 {is not really helping Black to stop White's activity:} 16. b4 axb3 17. Nxb3 Ra6 18. Qe1 e5 19. Bd2 $14 {.}) 16. b4 axb4 17. R5xb4 ({There was no point for} 17. axb4 $6 b6 18. Bb2 Ba6 19. Rd5 e6 20. Rxd4 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Bb7 $15 {. White is obliged to open the b-file, in order to activate his rooks and 'reveal' their combined force.}) 17... e5 18. Nb3 Kh7 19. a4 b6 20. Bd2 (20. Ba3 {is pointless:} Re8 21. a5 Bf8 22. Ra4 Bxa3 23. Rxa3 bxa5 24. Rba1 Bb7 {.}) 20... f5 21. a5 $1 bxa5 22. Rb5 (22. Ra4 Bb7 23. Bxa5 Qc8 $13 {.}) 22... e4 $2 {Black's desire to show her hand early in the centre is wrong.} ({She should opt for} 22... a4 $1 23. Ba5 Rxa5 24. Nxa5 Nc5 $5 {24...a3 25.Qa4 Ba6 26.R5b4 26.Qxa3 Bxb5 27.Rxb5 $14 Rf6 27.Qxa3 Bf8 28.Nb3 $14} 25. Bc6 $1 {25.Nc6?! Nxd3! 26.Qxd3 e4 27.Bxe4 fxe4 28.Qxe4 Bf5 29.Rxf5 gxf5 30.Qd5 Qf7 $17} Qa7 26. Bd5 Bd7 27. Nc6 Bxc6 28. Bxc6 e4 29. dxe4 fxe4 $13 {. Well, the desire to expand in the centre is tempting, but not always right…}) 23. Bxa5 $6 ({White missed an excellent chance with} 23. Bf4 $1 {, when Black has no satisfactory continuation at her disposal:} Qc6 {23...Be5 24.Nxd4 Ra6 25.Bxe5 Nxe5 26.dxe4 $16 , or 23...Qd8 24.dxe4 fxe4 25.Nxd4 $16} 24. dxe4 fxe4 25. Nxd4 Qxc4 26. Be3 $16 {.}) 23... Qc6 24. dxe4 $6 ({Although a natural response, White should have tried the complicated} 24. Rd5 $1 {, when Black has to be careful:} Re8 25. Bd2 $1 {25.dxe4 fxe4 26.Nxd4 Qxc4 27.Nc2 Nf6 28.Rd4 Qa2 29.Bb6 Rd7 30.Rxd7 Bxd7 31.Nb4 Qe6 32.Bd4 Rd8=} Nf6 26. Nxd4 Qa4 27. Rd6 Qxd1+ 28. Rxd1 exd3 29. Nb5 Ra4 30. Rxd3 Ne4 31. Rc1 $14 {.}) 24... fxe4 25. Nd2 ({Of course, White must avoid} 25. Nxd4 $2 {, as after} Qf6 $1 26. Bc3 {26.Ne2 Qxf2+ 27.Kh1 Ba6 $17} Ra3 27. R1b3 Rxb3 28. Rxb3 Qxf2+ 29. Kh1 Nc5 {, he will suffer,}) ({but} 25. Bb4 $5 {, was probably preferable:} Re8 26. Bc5 Nxc5 27. Rxc5 Qa8 28. Nxd4 Rd7 {28...Rd8 29.Rd5 Rxd5 30.cxd5 Qxd5 31.Nb5 Qxd1+ 32.Rxd1 Re7 33.Nd6 Bg4 34.Re1 $14} 29. Rd5 Rxd5 30. cxd5 Qxd5 31. Nc2 Qd3 32. Ne3 Re7 {.}) 25... Nf6 $6 ({Correct was} 25... Re8 26. Bb4 Bb7 27. Ra1 $13 {.}) 26. Bb6 Rd7 ({A bit better than} 26... Bg4 27. Nxe4 $1 {27.Qe1 Rd7 28.Nxe4 Nxe4 29.Bxe4 Qxc4=} Bxd1 28. Ng5+ hxg5 29. Bxc6 Ra4 30. Rxd1 Rxc4 31. Bg2 $14 {.}) 27. Re5 Qd6 ({A dead draw arises after} 27... Ng4 $5 28. Rc5 Qe6 29. Nxe4 Bb7 30. Qd3 Re7 31. f3 Ne5 32. Rxe5 Qxe5 33. Rb5 Qe6 34. Bc5 Rxf3 $1 35. Bxf3 Bxe4 36. Qxe4 Qxe4 37. Bxe4 Rxe4 38. Rb7 d3 39. Bf8 Kg8 40. Rxg7+ Kxf8 41. Rd7 Rxc4 42. Rxd3 {.}) 28. Ra5 $2 ({Too optimistic! White should have played} 28. f4 $1 exf3 {28...e3? 29.c5+- , traps the queen!} 29. Nxf3 Ng4 30. Bc5 Qc7 31. Bxf8 Nxe5 32. Bxg7 Kxg7 33. Nxe5 Qxe5 {,}) ({or} 28. Rxe4 $5 Nxe4 29. Nxe4 Qe6 30. Qd3 $13 {.}) 28... Qe6 29. Bc5 Re8 30. Rb6 Qf7 31. Qe2 $6 (31. Rb3 {was a must:} e3 32. fxe3 dxe3 33. Rxe3 {33.Bxe3 Qxc4 34.h3 Qe6 $17} Rxe3 34. Bxe3 Qe7 35. Bf2 Qb4 36. Ra2 Ng4 $17 {.}) 31... e3 $1 (31... d3 $6 32. Qd1 $13 {.}) 32. fxe3 dxe3 $2 ({Tempting, but quite strong was the alternative and natural} 32... Rxe3 $1 33. Qd1 Qe8 $1 34. Nf3 Ng4 {.}) 33. Nf1 {So, both sides have achieved their aims, as described in the early parts of the game: White has a passed c-pawn and Black an e-pawn. But Black's activity in her 'territory' seems to be far more dangerous.} Ng4 $1 34. Rb1 $2 {A heavy and losing blunder in heavy time-trouble!} ({White should also avoid} 34. Bc6 $2 Rd1 $1 35. Bxe8 Qxf1+ 36. Qxf1 e2 {, or}) (34. Qxg4 $2 e2 35. Rb1 Rd3 36. Qf4 Qxf4 37. gxf4 Rd1 {,}) ({but he should have opted for a complicated but fully justified line, starting by} 34. Bd5 $1 Rxd5 $1 {34...Qf2+ 35.Qxf2 exf2+ 36.Kg2 Rc7 37.Bd6 Rd7 38.Bc5 Rc7=} 35. cxd5 Qxd5 36. h3 Nf2 {36...Nf6!? 37.Rd6 37.Nxe3? Qe5-+ Qe5 38.Qxe3 Ne4= $13} 37. Nxe3 Nxh3+ 38. Kh2 Ng5 39. Nxd5 Rxe2+ 40. Kh1 Nf3 41. Bg1 Re1 42. Kg2 Nxg1 43. Ra7 {.}) 34... Rc7 $2 {Returning the favour due also to heavy time-trouble!} (34... Qf2+ 35. Qxf2 exf2+ 36. Kh1 {36.Bxf2 Nxf2 37.Kxf2 Bd4+ 38.Kf3 Rf7+ $17} Re1 37. Rab5 Rc7 {was winning.}) 35. Bd5 Qf5 (35... Qf2+ 36. Qxf2 exf2+ 37. Kg2 {37.Bxf2? Nxf2 38.Kxf2 Bd4+ 39.Kf3 h5 40.Ra2 Bh3-+} Bf5 38. Rb3 Re2 39. h3 $13 {.}) 36. Rb3 Nf2 $2 {Black cracks!} ({She should have gone for} 36... Qf2+ 37. Qxf2 exf2+ 38. Kg2 Bf5 $13 {.}) 37. Nxe3 Nh3+ 38. Kg2 Qg5 39. Qf3 Rxc5 $2 ({The last mistake, although} 39... Qd8 40. Kh1 Ng5 41. Qg2 $16 {was not pleasant either,}) ({but Black had to opt for} 39... Qe5 40. Bb6 Rd7 $13 {.}) 40. Rxc5 Qe7 (40... Rf8 41. Qxf8 Bxf8 42. Rxc8 {.}) 41. Rxc8 $1 Z0 ({Black resigned:} 41... Rxc8 42. Kxh3 {.}) 1-0

