1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Be7 5. Bb3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. c3 Be6 8. Ba4 Nd7 9. d4 exd4 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nxd4 c5 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Nd2 Nb6 14. Qe2 a5 15. f4 $1 {The pawn structures have defined the field of action for each side. White has a 4:3 majority on the kingside and Black a similar one on the queenside.} a4 16. Nf3 Qc8 {Intending to exchange queens via a6, which would defuse White's attacking potential and weaken the c4-square.} 17. Be3 Qa6 18. Rae1 Qxe2 19. Rxe2 Nc4 $6 {The pressure on b2 is ineffective.} (19... d5 $5 20. Bc1 Bf6 $1 {offers equal chances, but Black thought he was better.}) 20. Bc1 Rab8 21. g4 $1 {White sets his kingside majority in motion; in conjunction with his better placed pieces this will cause Black some problems. It must be noted that Black's majority is not as mobile. As a result, Black has ended up in a passive position.} Rf7 22. Rff2 c6 ({After} 22... g6 {, White would continue} 23. Kg2 Nb6 24. h4 $14 {.}) 23. f5 $1 exf5 24. exf5 g6 $6 ({Aiming to weaken the white pawn mass, but} 24... h6 25. h4 Bf8 {is preferable.}) 25. Re4 $1 Nb6 ({Compulsory, as} 25... d5 $2 {, would drop material after} 26. fxg6 hxg6 27. Re6 {, attacking two black pawns.}) 26. Bg5 $1 Bf8 27. fxg6 hxg6 28. Re6 $1 Kg7 29. Nh4 $1 Rxf2 30. Kxf2 Nc4 $1 {With a series of very good moves White has obtained the initiative. Black is obliged to seek immediate counterplay, as otherwise he will asphyxiate.} 31. Nxg6 $1 ({Best, as} 31. Bc1 $6 Kf7 $1 32. Rxg6 $2 Ne5 $1 {and 33...Nd3+!, would leave Black fully satisfied.}) 31... Rxb2+ 32. Kg3 Nd2 $2 {The text is threatening to force perpetual check with 33... Nf1+, but it is actually the losing move.} ({Good enough to preserve equality was} 32... Rxa2 $1 33. h4 Ra1 34. Rf6 Nd2 $13 {.}) 33. Kf4 $6 ({White would win the ending after} 33. Bxd2 $1 Rxd2 34. g5 $1 {34.Nxf8? Kxf8 35.h4 Rxa2 36.Rxd6 Rc2 37.Rxc6 Rxc3+ 38.Kf4 a3 39.Ra6 c4=} Kg8 35. h4 Bg7 36. h5 {, but the text also wins. White had a choice to make and from a practical viewpoint it would have been clearly preferable to opt for this endgame, where the possibility of going wrong is small.}) 33... Nf1 34. Kf5 $1 Rf2+ 35. Nf4 $6 {Time-trouble proves to be White's greatest enemy.} ({He could have won with} 35. Bf4 $1 Nxh2 36. g5 $1 {36.Rf6? Nxg4 37.Rxf8 Nh6+ 38.Ke6 Re2+! 39.Kxd6 Kxg6= , or 36.Re8? Nxg4 37.Kxg4 Kxg6 38.Rxf8 Rxa2=} Nf1 37. Nxf8 Kxf8 38. g6 Nd2 39. Rxd6 {.}) 35... Kf7 $1 36. Rf6+ Ke8 (36... Kg8 37. h3 $1 Ng3+ 38. Kg6 {would have left Black without chances to survive.}) 37. h3 $6 ({Defending the g4-pawn and thus neutralising the threatened 37...Ne3+!, but} 37. h4 $1 Ne3+ 38. Ke6 Nxg4 39. Rf7 Rf1 40. Ra7 {seems to be great and sealing Black's fate...}) 37... Rxa2 38. Bh4 $2 {Another mistake induced by time-trouble.} (38. Kg6 $1 {wins.}) 38... a3 $2 (38... Ne3+ $1 39. Kg6 Nd5 $1 40. Nxd5 cxd5 41. Rf4 Rh2 42. Rxa4 Rxh3 43. Bf6 Kd7 {should hold for Black.}) 39. Ne6 $2 {This mistake is fatal, leaving White lost.} ({White could still prevail by} 39. Kg6 $1 Nd2 40. Ne6 {.}) 39... Be7 $1 40. Ng7+ Kd7 41. Rf7 Re2 $1 42. Kg6 Z0 ({White resigned in view of} 42... a2 43. Rxf1 Bxh4 44. Ra1 Be1 {. His ideas were good, their implementation even better, but his final effort missed the target. One must also not forget about the negative role of the mutual time-trouble that has destroyed a lot of good games, but this is just a part of the game!}) 0-1

