{The next example can hardly be classified under one of the previous classifications. It looks like more than a minority attack, although it has little common with it. Well, it is good be called one of these mysterious, but often met cases…} 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 Bf5 3. cxd5 Bxb1 4. Qa4+ c6 5. Rxb1 Qxd5 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. Bd2 Ngf6 8. e3 e6 9. Rc1 Ne4 10. Bc4 Qd6 11. Qb3 Nb6 12. Be2 Nxd2 13. Nxd2 e5 {The text looks natural, but now we have two different pawn majorities, one for each opponent. White's majority is more flexible and thus this gives him the advantage.} (13... Be7 {could also be played:} 14. O-O O-O 15. Rfd1 $14 {.}) 14. dxe5 $1 ({The optimistic} 14. Nc4 $6 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 Qb4+ $1 16. Ke2 Qxb3 17. Bxb3 exd4 18. exd4 {only leads to equality and is therefore mistaken.}) 14... Qxe5 15. O-O Bd6 16. Nf3 Qe7 17. Nd4 $1 g6 18. Bf3 $1 {White has already determined his plan, which consists of a queenside minority attack. Therefore, he places his pieces in such a way that they will be able to fully cooperate in line with this plan.} O-O 19. Rfd1 Rad8 20. a4 $1 (20. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 21. Nxc6 {is possible:} Qf6 22. Nxd8 Rxd8 23. g3 $14 {.}) 20... Bc7 $2 ({Black also loses after} 20... Na8 $2 21. a5 a6 22. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 23. Nxc6 $16 {,}) ({but he had to play} 20... Qe5 $1 21. g3 Bb8 $1 22. Qc2 {(intending b4)} Qa5 23. b3 Be5 24. Qc5 $14 {, with a slight advantage for White.}) 21. a5 Nd5 22. a6 $1 Qe5 23. g3 {Black's queenside pawn structure is now destroyed.} Qf6 24. axb7 Ne7 25. Nxc6 Nxc6 26. Bxc6 Bb6 27. Bd7 {As heavy material was lost, Black decided to call it a day…} 1-0

