1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 Be7 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Be3 Na6 9. O-O Nc5 10. Qf3 a6 11. Rad1 Qc7 12. g4 Rb8 13. a4 Nxb3 14. cxb3 Nd7 15. g5 Ne5 16. Qg2 Nc6 17. f4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 {Black has a clear-cut 5:4 majority on the kingside, while White cannot claim the same on the queenside; his doubled b-pawns deny him his 'rightful' majority. Black's main plan is simple: transition to an ending, where he will be able to exploit what is practically an extra pawn.} f5 $1 {An excellent move, stopping White's initiative in its tracks and allowing Black to exchange pieces, further approaching an endgame where he will enjoy the advantages of a better structure and better minor piece (bishop vs. knight).} 19. gxf6 ({Black would also be happy after} 19. exf5 Rxf5 $15 {.}) 19... Bxf6 20. Bxf6 Rxf6 21. f5 $2 {The last mistake.} ({White had to try} 21. Qd2 d5 $1 22. exd5 Bd7 $1 23. dxe6 Bxe6 $15 {.}) 21... Bd7 $1 22. b4 Rbf8 23. Qg3 Qb6+ 24. Rf2 d5 $1 {A decisive breakthrough, destroying White's pawn structure and the white position in general.} 25. exd5 Rxf5 26. Rdd2 h6 $1 27. h4 Rxf2 28. Rxf2 Rxf2 29. Qxf2 Qxb4 {Black has won material without surrendering his advantages.} 30. Qe3 exd5 31. Qe5 Qg4+ 32. Kf1 Bc6 33. Ne2 Qe4 34. Qxe4 dxe4 {White could resign here, but he decided to play until the first-time control was reached. A common ‘strategy’ in a lot of cases, as the losing side has nothing to lose further!} 35. Nc3 a5 36. Kf2 Kf7 37. b3 Kf6 38. Ke3 Kf5 39. Ne2 Kg4 40. Nd4 Bd5 {And now White decided that he had enough…} 0-1

