1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. a3 Bb7 5. Nc3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Rc1 Nbd7 10. Bb5 c6 11. Bd3 c5 12. O-O a6 13. Qc2 h6 14. Bf4 Re8 15. Rfd1 c4 16. Bf5 Nf8 17. Ne5 Nh5 18. Bg4 Nxf4 19. exf4 Bf6 20. Bf3 b5 {An interesting position, where Black possesses the bishop pair and a healthier pawn structure, while his queenside majority seems to be ready to advance. So, you might easily get the illusion that Black stands better; chess can be a tricky game as well! The secret here that keeps White into the game, is his centralised pieces and in general his central pressure, especially against the black d5-pawn.} 21. b3 $1 {A well-known mechanism to stop Black's queenside majority from advancing.} Rb8 22. g3 Ne6 23. Bg2 Qd6 24. bxc4 bxc4 ({Black will anyway get a passed and protected pawn on c4, but how to re-capture? It seems that} 24... dxc4 {should be preferred, but White seems to have good play after} 25. Bxb7 Rxb7 26. Ne4 $13 {, due to his centralised pieces. After the text, Black's queenside majority has been 'destroyed', while his c4-pawn goes nowhere, at least for the time-being. Well, certainly White is not standing better; the position can be considered as unclear with mutual chances. And this can be considered a success, as to the facts and 'evaluation' of the first diagram.}) 25. Qa4 $1 Red8 26. Rb1 Be7 $6 ({Black didn't like} 26... Ba8 27. Rxb8 Rxb8 {due to} 28. Nd7 Rd8 29. Nxf6+ gxf6 30. Qa5 $13 {, but still he had to go for it.}) 27. Rxb7 $1 {A nice exchange sacrifice, which gives White the upper hand.} Rxb7 28. Bxd5 $6 (28. Nxd5 $1 {was better:} Qxa3 $1 29. Nxe7+ Qxe7 30. Nc6 {30.Bxb7 Qxb7 31.Qxc4 Qd5=} Qe8 31. Re1 Rdb8 32. Be4 Qd7 33. Qxc4 $14 {.}) 28... Rb3 $1 {Forcing exchanges.} 29. Bxe6 Qxe6 30. d5 Qd6 $2 ({Again, Black missed his best continuation by} 30... Qf5 $1 31. Nc6 Qc2 32. Nxd8 Rxc3 33. Qe8+ Kh7 34. Re1 Bxd8 35. Qxd8 Rf3 36. Rf1 Qf5 {.}) 31. Qxc4 Rxc3 ({White should prevail after} 31... Rxa3 32. Ne4 Qb4 33. d6 Qxc4 34. Nxc4 Rb3 35. Ned2 $1 Rb7 36. dxe7 Rxe7 37. Ra1 {, so Black decided to return the exchange, hoping to be saved in the endgame.}) 32. Qxc3 Qxa3 33. Qc4 $2 ({Quite strong was} 33. Qc7 $1 Qd6 34. Qa7 {and probably Black will not survive...}) 33... Bd6 $1 34. Qc6 Qb3 35. Re1 $2 ({A second blunder in (nearly) a row. White had to opt for the natural} 35. Rd4 Qb1+ 36. Kg2 Bxe5 37. fxe5 Qf5 38. Qxa6 Qxe5 39. Rd1 Rd6 40. Qa8+ Kh7 $16 {, where he would have good chances to prevail.}) 35... Bxe5 $1 36. Rxe5 Qb5 $1 37. Qxb5 axb5 38. d6 b4 (38... b4 {Draw agreed, as after} 39. Rb5 Rxd6 40. Rxb4 {, White's extra doubled f-pawn is not enough for the advantage.}) 1/2-1/2

