1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 Ne4 7. Qc2 Nc6 8. e3 e5 9. Nf3 Bf5 10. Bd3 exd4 11. O-O Bg6 12. exd4 O-O 13. b4 Re8 14. c5 a6 15. Bb2 Ng5 16. Ne5 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Qf6 18. Rae1 Rad8 19. Qd1 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Qf5 21. f4 Ne4 22. Bd4 {Black has successfully blockaded White's pawn majority on the kingside. Generally, the queen cannot be considered an ideal blockading force but here it operates quite well. Black has only to be concerned with White's main idea: the g4 advance, which will unblock the majority.} Re6 $1 23. Re3 ({With his previous move, Black stopped} 23. g4 $2 {due to} Rg6 24. h3 h5 {.}) 23... Rg6 24. Qe1 Rc8 $1 {A nice plan to come in the future is to try to open a file on the queenside. And this is the logical approach, as play on the kingside is temporarily frozen.} 25. Qe2 h5 26. Kh1 Ra8 27. Rd3 b6 {Here it comes.} 28. Be3 ({The opening of the c-file with} 28. cxb6 cxb6 {would be to Black's benefit:} 29. Bb2 Rc8 $17 {, when} 30. Rxd5 $2 {fails to} Rc2 {.}) 28... b5 $1 {With the idea ...a5, opening the a-file.} (28... bxc5 29. Bxc5 c6 30. Bb6 {allows White to defend.}) 29. a4 $2 ({White cannot grab the important d5-pawn:} 29. Rxd5 $6 Nc3 30. Qd3 Qg4 31. Rd8+ Kh7 $1 {31...Rxd8? 32.Qxd8+ Kh7 33.Qd2 $16} 32. Rg1 {32.Qxg6+? fxg6 33.Rxa8 Qe2-+ , or 32.Rf2? Rxd8 33.Qxd8 Nd1-+} Rxd8 33. Qxd8 Ne2 34. f5 Qxf5 $17 {,}) ({but he should have gone for} 29. c6 $5 {, aiming for some activity.}) 29... bxa4 $1 30. Ra1 Rb8 ({Not bad, but} 30... h4 $1 31. Rxa4 h3 32. g3 Rxg3 {would have been curtains.}) 31. Rxa4 (31. Rxd5 Nc3 32. Qd3 Qg4 33. Rd8+ Kh7 34. Qxg6+ Qxg6 35. Rxb8 a3 {.}) 31... d4 $2 (31... h4 {and ...h3 was a killer.}) 32. Bxd4 (32. Rxd4 $2 Nc3 {,}) ({or} 32. Bd2 $2 Nf2+ {.}) 32... Qxf4 33. Rf3 $6 (33. Qf3 $6 Qh4 $17 {was also bad,}) ({but White could have questioned Black's 31st move by} 33. g3 $1 Qf5 34. Qf3 $15 {.}) 33... Qg4 34. Re3 $6 ({Although not fully satisfactory, White had to opt for} 34. Rxa6 Nf2+ $1 35. Qxf2 Rxa6 $17 {.}) 34... Qd7 $6 ({Black again missed a winning combination:} 34... Nf2+ $1 35. Qxf2 Qd1+ 36. Re1 {36.Qe1 Qxa4-+} Qxa4 {.}) 35. Ra2 (35. Rxe4 Qxa4 36. e6 Qb3 {.}) 35... Rxb4 {At least Black has won a pawn while keeping the favourable pawn structure.} 36. Rxe4 Rxd4 37. Rxd4 Qxd4 38. Rd2 Qg4 (38... Qf4 $5 39. Rd8+ Kh7 $17 40. Qxh5+ $2 Rh6 {.}) 39. Qxg4 Rxg4 {The rook ending is won for Black but still some technique is needed to secure the full point!} 40. Rd8+ Kh7 41. Rd7 Rc4 42. Kg1 Rxc5 43. Rxf7 Kg6 44. e6 a5 45. Rf8 Re5 46. Ra8 (46. Rc8 Rxe6 47. Rxc7 Ra6 {.}) 46... Kf6 $1 47. Ra6 g5 48. Kf2 c5 {The white king is cut off from the queenside, so the win for Black is quite easy.} 49. Kf3 (49. Rxa5 Kxe6 50. Ra8 Kd5 {.}) 49... c4 50. Rc6 a4 (50... Rxe6 51. Rxc4 Ra6 52. Ra4 Ke5 53. Ke3 Kd5 54. Kd3 Kc5 55. Ra1 {55.Kc3 Kb5 56.Kb3 Re6 57.Rd4 Re3+ 58.Kb2 Re2+ 59.Kb3 Rxg2 60.Rd5+ Kb6 61.h4 gxh4 62.Rxh5 Rg4-+} a4 56. Kc3 a3 57. Kb3 a2 58. Kb2 Kb4 {.}) 51. Ra6 (51. Rxc4 Ra5 52. Re4 {52.Rc2 a3 53.Ra2 Kxe6-+} Ke7 53. Re2 a3 54. Ra2 Kxe6 55. Ke4 Ra4+ 56. Kd3 Kd5 57. Kc3 Ra8 58. Kb3 Ke4 59. Re2+ Kd3 60. Ra2 Rb8+ {.}) 51... a3 52. g3 (52. Rxa3 Kxe6 53. Ra8 Kd5 {.}) 52... a2 53. h4 g4+ 54. Kf4 Re2 {An excellent middlegame strategy and great endgame play! GM Jan Timman was supposed to be probably the best ‘western’ player at in 1985-1995 and his efforts were crowned for playing the final of the FIDE World Championship in 1993, against Anatoly Karpov. He was fearless and ready to play every game and against anyone for challenging the win. And this element made him a difficult opponent for anyone…} 0-1

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 1: Pawn "]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.05.28"]
