[White "3) The Majority in the Endgam"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. Z0 {The endgame is the stage of the game that the mobile majority and the potential passed pawn can give effective results. Even at the very late stages of the game a majority can be useful. In combination with other elements, it can be proven lethal… To examine the subject, we must clarify that when we refer to ‘queenside majority’ we mean the opposite side of which the kings are located. So, this is the odd-one-out of the various strategic elements. Why did the 1st FIDE World Champion, William Steinitz, pick a queenside pawn majority as one of the most important strategic concepts? Why isn't the kingside majority, or the central majority, more important? To clarify again, the central majority is more important for most of the game. However, as the game nears the endgame, a queenside pawn majority becomes more and more important. The reason lies in the potential for creating passed pawns. As we know, it is easiest to create a passed pawn if you have a pawn majority. However, since in most games the king (s) castles short, both kings are further away from the queenside. And without kings, a pawn breakthrough becomes easier, since there is no enemy king to hamper the creation of a passed pawn. That is why kingside majorities are less valuable in the endgame - the king can stop pawns on his own. The queenside majority is often an advantage because it is more likely to create an outside passed pawn. A chess player, who wishes to excel in the game, should be alert of the correct handling of such positions. The examples to follow give a clear way of this concept and serve our purposes to the maximum. FIDE World Champion Anatoly Karpov many times has proved that he knows exactly what to do and where and how to place his pieces.} *

