1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d5 6. c4 dxc4 7. Na3 c3 8. bxc3 c5 9. Nc4 Nc6 10. Bb2 Be6 11. Nce5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bd5 14. Qd3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qd5+ 16. Qf3 e6 17. Rfc1 Rfc8 18. e3 h5 19. h3 Bf8 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. f3 Bb4 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Rc1 Rxc1 24. Bxc1 Kf8 {The position seems to be level. White will try his chances in the centre and the kingside, while Black will be based on his queenside pawn majority.} 25. g4 hxg4 26. hxg4 Ke7 27. Nd3 Bd6 28. g5 Nd7 29. e4 $1 dxe4 $6 {Although not the losing mistake, Black had to avoid giving White a strong central duo.} ({Better was} 29... Nb6 30. Kf2 Nc4 31. Bf4 a5 {.}) 30. fxe4 Ke8 31. Kf3 b5 {What else? Black has to seek for counterplay with his only asset; the queenside majority.} 32. e5 Be7 33. Ke4 {Centralisation!} Nf8 $1 {Putting pressure on the g5-pawn.} 34. Ne1 $1 Ne6 35. Nf3 b4 $2 {The decisive mistake.} ({Black should hold after} 35... a5 36. d5 Nc5+ 37. Kd4 Kd7 {.}) 36. Kd3 (36. Kd5 a5 37. Kc4 $16 {was good as well.}) 36... a5 37. Kc4 a4 38. d5 $1 {Now White's active king decides the outcome.} Nc5 $6 {Based on a miscalculation.} 39. d6 $1 Ne4 (39... b3 40. Kxc5 bxa2 41. Bb2 {.}) 40. dxe7 b3 41. axb3 axb3 42. Ba3 b2 43. Bxb2 Kxe7 44. Kd5 {The rest are not difficult.} Nf2 45. Bd4 Nh1 46. Be3 Ng3 47. Nd4 Nh5 48. Bd2 Kf8 49. Ne2 Ng7 50. Bb4+ Ke8 51. Ng3 Ne6 52. Ne4 Nf4+ 53. Kc6 Nd3 54. Bd6 Kd8 55. Nc5 Nb4+ 56. Kb5 Nd5 57. Kc4 Ne3+ 58. Kd4 Nf5+ 59. Kd5 Ne3+ 60. Kc6 Ke8 61. Ne4 Kd8 62. Nf6 Nf5 63. Bc5 Ng7 64. Nd5 Ne6 65. Be7+ Kc8 66. Nb6+ Kb8 67. Kd7 Kb7 68. Nc4 Nf4 69. Nd6+ 1-0

