1. d4 {[%mdl 32768] During the 2008 Wijk aan Zee prestigious tournament edition, I was talking with Magnus Carlsen on the variation he choose. I was quite pleased when he told me that he studied my recently published book ‘Beating the Fianchetto Defences’ (Gambit 2006) and particularly the previous endgame, which helped him to win the following one!} Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. Bh4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Qa4+ Qd7 9. Qxc4 b6 10. e3 Ba6 11. Qb3 Bxf1 12. Kxf1 O-O 13. Ke2 c5 14. dxc5 Na6 15. Rhd1 Qb7 16. c6 $1 Qxc6 17. Bxe7 Rfe8 18. Ba3 Qxc3 19. Qxc3 Bxc3 20. Rac1 {White has been placed more harmoniously, as his rooks are on open files, while his centre is more compact. He should hold a small but pleasant advantage.} Bb4 ({Black must get control of the c5-square. After} 20... Bg7 21. Nd4 {, he is suffering.}) 21. Bb2 ({White correctly preserves all pieces on the board, although not bad is the alternative} 21. Bxb4 Nxb4 22. Rd4 {( 22.a3 Na6 23.Nd4 Nc5 24.Nb5 Re5 25.Rc4 $14 ) ( 22.Rc4 Na6 23.Nd4 $14 )} Na6 23. Ne1 Red8 {( 23...Rac8 24.Rxc8 Rxc8 25.Ra4 $16 ) ( 23...Rad8 24.Ra4 $16 )} 24. Nd3 Rxd4 25. exd4 Re8+ 26. Kd2 Rd8 27. Rc4 $14 {.}) 21... Bf8 22. Nd4 Nc5 $6 ({Preferable was} 22... Rac8 $1 23. Nb5 Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Nc5 25. Rd1 Rc8 {, when Black is near to equality.}) 23. g4 $1 ({Not helpful is} 23. Nb3 $6 Ne6 24. Rd7 Red8 25. Rb7 Rdb8) ({But maybe White could also try} 23. Nb5 Rad8 24. Nc7 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rc8 26. Nd5 $14 {. The text is logical; White gains space on the kingside. As this is still a queenless middlegame White seems to have better prospects anyway. His pieces are well placed and he can mobilise his kingside pawn majority more effectively than Black can do with his own queenside pawn majority.}) 23... Re4 $6 ({Doubling rooks along the semi-closed e-file cannot be the right plan for Black. Better is} 23... Rad8 24. Nb5 $14 {.}) 24. Kf3 Rae8 25. h3 f6 26. Ba3 $1 Kf7 27. Rc2 Na6 ({Black is sort of good moves:} 27... h5 28. Nc6 hxg4+ 29. hxg4 a6 30. Bxc5 $1 Bxc5 31. Rd7+ Kg8 32. Rb7 Ra4 33. Nb8 $16 {, but now White is ample to penetrate into Black's camp.}) 28. Bxf8 Kxf8 29. Rc6 ({Also good is} 29. Nc6 Nb4 30. Nxb4 Rxb4 31. Rc7 Re7 32. Rd8+ Kf7 33. Rdd7 Rxd7 34. Rxd7+ Ke6 35. Rxa7 h5 36. gxh5 gxh5 37. a3 $16 {.}) 29... Kg7 30. Nb5 ({Also good is} 30. a4 R4e5 31. Rd6 Nc5 32. Nc6 Re4 33. R1d4 $16 {.}) 30... R4e7 31. Rdd6 Nc5 (31... Nb4 32. Rc3 Nxa2 33. Ra3 Nb4 34. Rxa7 Rxa7 35. Nxa7 Rb8 36. Rd7+ Kg8 37. Rd4 $16 {.}) 32. Nc7 ({Not} 32. Rxf6 $2 Nd7 33. Rfd6 Ne5+ 34. Kg3 Nxc6 35. Rxc6 Rd7 $17 {.}) 32... Rf8 33. h4 $1 ({Winning a pawn by} 33. Rxc5 $6 bxc5 34. Ne6+ Rxe6 35. Rxe6 Rc8 $1 36. Re7+ Kh6 37. Rxa7 {, is not advisable, as Black seems to have create enough counterplay:} c4 38. Ke2 c3 39. Kd1 Rd8+ 40. Kc2 Rd2+ 41. Kxc3 Rxf2 42. a4 Rf3 {. White keeps the pressure on.}) 33... Rff7 ({Interesting is} 33... f5 {. After} 34. g5 Re4 35. h5 {( 35.Rxc5 bxc5 36.Ne6+ Kf7 37.Nxf8 Kxf8 38.Ra6 Rxh4 39.Rxa7 Rg4! ( 39...Rh5? 40.Kf4 c4 41.Ke5 Rh2 42.Kf6 Ke8 43.f4 c3 44.Rc7 c2 45.Kg7+- ) 40.Rxh7 Rxg5= )} gxh5 36. g6 hxg6 {( 36...h6 37.Nd5+- )} 37. Rxg6+ Kh7 38. Rh6+ Kg7 39. Nb5 $16 {, Black is still in trouble...}) 34. Nd5 Rd7 35. Rxd7 (35. e4 {, is possible:} Rxd6 36. Rxd6 Nd3 {( 36...Rd7? 37.Nxf6 Rxd6 38.Ne8++- )} 37. h5 $16 {.}) 35... Nxd7 (35... Rxd7 $2 36. Nxf6 Rf7 37. g5 Nd7 38. Ke4 $1 Nxf6+ 39. gxf6+ Rxf6 40. Rxf6 Kxf6 41. Kd5 Ke7 42. Kc6 Ke6 43. a4 {.}) 36. Kg3 {The remaining white forces are much more active and White stands clearly better.} Nc5 37. f3 h6 38. Nf4 g5 ({Or} 38... Kh7 39. e4 Nd7 40. h5 g5 41. Nd5 $16 {.}) 39. Nh5+ Kg6 40. f4 ({Good enough, but} 40. Kh3 $1 Nd7 41. Rd6 Re7 42. Ng3 {, should be curtains!}) 40... gxf4+ (40... Kh7 41. Kg2 $1 Ne4 42. Re6 Nc5 43. Nxf6+ {.}) 41. exf4 Kh7 (41... Ne4+ 42. Kf3 Re7 43. f5+ Kf7 44. Kf4 b5 45. Re6 {.}) 42. f5 Kg8 43. Kf3 $1 (43. Nxf6+ $2 Rxf6 44. Rxf6 Ne4+ {.}) 43... Nd7 44. Ke4 (44. Kf4 $1 Kf8 45. Rc8+ Ke7 46. Rh8 {.}) 44... Kf8 (44... Nc5+ 45. Kd4 Rd7+ 46. Kc4 {.}) 45. Rc8+ Ke7 46. Kd5 {Active white pieces against black passive pieces and weaknesses (h6). The end should not be far away.} b5 47. Rh8 Nb6+ 48. Kc6 ({Even better was} 48. Kd4 Nd7 49. Rxh6 b4 50. Nf4 {.}) 48... Nc4 49. Ra8 $1 (49. Rxh6 $2 Ne5+ 50. Kxb5 Nxg4 {, is not clear.}) 49... Ne5+ 50. Kc5 Nd7+ (50... Nxg4 {, loses to} 51. Rxa7+ Ke8 52. Rxf7 Kxf7 53. Kxb5 {.}) 51. Kxb5 Kd6 52. Rxa7 Rf8 53. Kb4 Nc5 (53... Ne5 54. Ra6+ Kc7 55. Nxf6 Nc6+ 56. Rxc6+ Kxc6 57. g5 {.}) 54. Kc4 1-0

