1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. a3 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Qc2 Be7 8. e4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. Bd3 c5 11. Bb2 Qc8 12. Qe2 Ba6 13. O-O Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Qa6 15. Qxa6 Nxa6 16. Ne5 Rfc8 17. Rfd1 cxd4 18. cxd4 Rc2 19. Nd3 Rac8 20. Rac1 Kf8 21. Kf1 Ke8 22. Rxc2 Rxc2 23. Rc1 Rxc1+ 24. Nxc1 {Black chances seem to be better, mainly due to the possibility of creating an outside passed pawn, thanks to his queenside pawn majority. But of course there are many things to be done firstly; without creating further weaknesses it would be difficult to prevail.} f5 $1 25. f3 (25. exf5 $6 exf5 26. Ke2 b5 $17 {, should be even worse for White, due to his isolated d-pawn.}) 25... fxe4 26. fxe4 e5 $1 {A nice small strategical tactic!} 27. Nb3 ({After} 27. dxe5 Nc5 {, Black regains his pawn and the white passed e-pawn is a mere weakness as well.}) 27... exd4 28. Nxd4 {Black succeeded to create weaknesses in the white camp (e4-a3). Now he must improve his pieces and then activate his own (future) passed pawn on the queenside.} Bf6 $1 (28... Nc5 $2 {, would be a bad idea due to} 29. Nc6 {.}) 29. Ke2 Nc5 30. Ke3 Ne6 $1 31. Nxe6 $2 ({White had to stay put with} 31. Bc3 Nxd4 32. Bxd4 Kf7 $1 {( 32...Bxd4+? 33.Kxd4 and it is White who is winning!)} 33. e5 $1 {( 33.Bxf6? Kxf6 34.Kd4 Ke6 35.g3 h5 36.Kc4 a6 37.Kd4 Kd6 38.e5+ Ke6-+ )} Be7 34. a4 Ke6 35. Ke4 {Where he could put-up a quite stubborn defence:} Bb4 $1 {( 35...Bc5?! 36.Bxc5! ( 36.Bb2? a6 and the outside passed pawn will decide. A sample variation is 37.Bc3 ( 37.h3? b5 38.axb5 axb5 39.Bc1 b4 40.Bb2 Bf2 41.Kd3 Bg3 42.Ke4 Be1 43.Kd3 Bc3 44.Bxc3 bxc3 45.Kxc3 Kxe5-+ ) 37...Bf2 38.g4 b5 39.axb5 axb5 40.Bd2 Bc5 $17 ) 36...bxc5 37.h4 h5 38.Kf4 c4 39.Ke4 c3 40.Kd3 Kxe5 41.Kxc3 Kf4 42.Kb4 Kg3 43.Kb5 Kxg2 44.Ka6 Kg3 45.Kxa7 Kxh4 46.a5 g5 47.a6 g4 48.Kb6 g3 49.a7 g2 50.a8=Q g1=Q+ 51.Kc7= )} 36. g4 g6 {( 36...Ba5 37.Kd3 Kd5 38.e6= )} 37. h3 Ba5 38. h4 a6 39. h5 b5 40. axb5 axb5 41. hxg6 hxg6 42. Bb2 Be1 $15 {/. The variations are quite lengthy and it is easily for White to go astray, as ultimate precision is rather important…}) 31... Bxb2 32. a4 Ke7 33. Nc7 Be5 34. Nd5+ Kd6 {Black is plain winning. He has a good bishop vs. a bad knight endgame, plus his future outside passed pawn.} 35. h3 Kc5 36. Kd3 a6 37. Ne3 b5 38. axb5 axb5 $2 (38... Kxb5 $1 {, looks right as the black passed pawn will be on the a- rather in the b-file:} 39. Nc4 Bg3 40. Nb2 a5 {.}) 39. Nd5 $2 ({White missed his salvation by} 39. Nc2 $1 b4 40. Ne1 b3 41. Nf3 b2 42. Kc2 Bc3 43. g4 {.}) 39... b4 40. Ne3 b3 41. Nc4 b2 42. Nd2 h5 $1 {Black's plan now is to attack the kingside pawns with his king, but first advances his pawns so they will be closer to queening.} 43. g4 Bf4 44. Nb1 h4 $1 {Preserving pawns!} 45. Kc3 Be5+ 46. Kd3 Bd4 47. Nd2 Bf6 48. Kc2 ({Or} 48. Nb1 Kd6 49. Ke3 Ke5 50. Na3 Bg5+ {and the black king penetrates.}) 48... Kd4 $1 49. g5 ({If} 49. Kxb2 {, then} Kd3+ 50. Kc1 Bg5 {.}) 49... Be5 $1 50. Nf3+ Kxe4 51. Nxh4 Bc3 $1 ({Black should avoid a last trick:} 51... Ke3 $2 52. Ng6 $1 {( 52.g6? Kf2 53.Nf5 Kf3 54.Ne7 Kg3 55.Nc6 Bf6-+ ( 55...Bc3? 56.Nd8! Kxh3 57.Nf7 Kh4 58.Nh8= )} Bc3 53. Kb1 Kf3 54. Nh8 $1 Kg3 55. g6 Kxh3 56. Kc2 {and the position is drawn, as White cannot win the white g-pawn!}) (51... Bc3 {Here White resigned due to} 52. Ng2 {( 52.g6 Bf6 53.Ng2 Kf3 54.Ne1+ Ke2 55.Ng2 Bg5 56.Kxb2 Kf2-+ )} Kf3 53. Nh4+ Kf4 {.}) 0-1

