1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f4 Qc7 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Bf3 O-O 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Na4 Nd7 13. c4 c5 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Qc2 Bf6 16. Rad1 Rfd8 17. Rd3 Rac8 18. b3 Nb8 19. e5 dxe5 20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Ne4 Be7 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. fxe5 Nd7 24. Rd1 Qc7 25. Qc3 h6 26. h3 Qc6 27. Nf2 Qc7 28. Ne4 Qc6 29. Nf2 Qc7 30. Bf4 Nf8 31. Rxd8 Qxd8 32. Nd3 Qc7 33. Qe1 Qd8 34. Qe4 Qa5 35. Qe2 Ng6 36. Bg3 Nf8 37. Be1 Qc7 38. Qe4 Qd8 {In this simplified position, both majorities seem difficult to move. But White thought up a very strong and efficient plan - to move his king to the queenside in order to support his pieces and his majority!} 39. Kf1 $1 Qc8 40. Ke2 Nd7 41. Kd1 Bf8 ({Black tries to put up a counter defence, planning ...g6 and ...Bg7, putting pressure on White's e-pawn. The alternative was} 41... f5 42. exf6 Nxf6 43. Qf3 $16 {, as Black would have been full of weak pawns.}) 42. Kc2 g6 ({After} 42... Qc7 43. a3 a5 44. Bc3 Qa7 45. Qc6 {, Black is tied down to passivity.}) 43. Bc3 Bg7 44. a3 $1 {All according to the initial plan.} Bf8 45. b4 cxb4 (45... Nb6 46. Kb3 Qd7 47. Nb2 {, is similar to the game.}) 46. axb4 Nb6 47. Kb3 Qe8 48. Nb2 {White protected his weak points and his queenside pawns are ready now to roll.} Qd7 49. Bd4 Nc8 50. Be3 Ne7 51. Qa8 $1 Qc6 ({Black's hand was more or less forced:} 51... Nc6 $2 52. Bxh6) ({Or} 51... Kg7 $2 52. Bxh6+ Kxh6 53. Qxf8+) ({Or, finally} 51... g5 $6 52. Bc5 {. But now the white king will have no counterpart...}) 52. Qxc6 Nxc6 53. Nd3 Bg7 54. Ka4 $1 (54. Bf4 {, was not bad either, but White is not losing time!}) 54... Kf8 ({All other continuations lose rather easily:} 54... Bxe5 $2 55. b5) ({Or} 54... f6 $2 55. exf6 Bxf6 56. Nc5) ({Or finally} 54... Nxe5 $2 55. Nxe5 Bxe5 56. Ka5 Bc3 57. Bc5 {.}) 55. Bc5+ Ke8 56. Bd6 f6 $6 ({More tenacious was} 56... Kd7 57. b5 axb5+ 58. cxb5 Nd8 59. Nc5+ Kc8 60. b6 Nb7 61. Ne4 f6 {( 61...Kd7 62.Kb5 $16 )} 62. exf6 Bxf6 63. Kb5 $16 {, although it would be difficult for Black to avoid defeat in the long run.}) 57. exf6 Bxf6 58. Nc5 {A pawn is now lost.} e5 59. Nxa6 e4 60. b5 Be5 $5 61. Bc5 Nd4 62. Bxd4 $1 Bxd4 63. Kb3 Kd7 64. c5 h5 65. g4 hxg4 66. hxg4 g5 67. Kc4 e3 68. Kd3 Kc8 (68... Ke6 69. b6 {.}) 69. c6 {A game of a clear-cut and effective endgame plan: activation of the majority with the idea of creating a passed pawn. How simple it looked...} 1-0

