1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Rc1 Re8 8. Qc2 c6 9. Bd3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd5 11. Bxe7 Rxe7 12. O-O Nf8 13. Rfd1 Bd7 14. e4 Nb6 15. Bf1 Rc8 16. b4 {The beginning of a type of 'minority attack', with the a- and b-pawns being used against the black a-, b- and c-pawns.} Be8 17. Qb3 Rec7 18. a4 Ng6 19. a5 $1 Nd7 20. e5 $1 {Creating a strong outpost on d6; a white knight will land soon on it!} b6 21. Ne4 Rb8 22. Qc3 Nf4 23. Nd6 Nd5 24. Qa3 f6 {White is surely in the driver's seat and the following exchanges transforms his advantage in something 'more' concrete...} 25. Nxe8 $1 Qxe8 26. exf6 gxf6 27. b5 $1 Rbc8 ({Or} 27... c5 28. dxc5 Nxc5 29. Bc4 Qh5 30. Nd4 $16 {.}) 28. bxc6 Rxc6 29. Rxc6 Rxc6 30. axb6 axb6 {It looks like (as L.Pachman points out) 'White has apparently merely helped Black to achieve his strategical aim of obtaining a passed pawn from his queenside majority'. But of course, isolated passed pawns can be either weak or strong, and Black's b- and e-pawns are clearly weak here.} 31. Re1 Qc8 32. Nd2 Nf8 33. Ne4 Qd8 34. h4 Rc7 35. Qb3 Rg7 36. g3 Ra7 37. Bc4 {White slowly improves his position while Black just hangs around with his rook...} Ra5 38. Nc3 $1 Nxc3 ({Or} 38... Qd6 39. Nxd5 exd5 40. Bd3 Ra3 41. Qd1 {.}) 39. Qxc3 Kf7 40. Qe3 Qd6 41. Qe4 Ra4 42. Qb7+ Kg6 43. Qc8 $6 (43. h5+ $1 {was accurate:} Kh6 {43...Kxh5 44.Qg7 Ng6 45.Re4+-} 44. Qf7 Rxc4 45. Qxf6+ Ng6 46. hxg6 hxg6 47. Qh8+ Kg5 48. Re5+ Kg4 49. Qh4+ Kf3 50. Qf4# {.}) 43... Qb4 44. Rc1 Qe7 45. Bd3+ Kh6 46. Rc7 Ra1+ 47. Kg2 Qd6 48. Qxf8+ $1 {Black resigned: 48...Qxf8 49.Rxh7 .} 1-0

