1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 g6 4. Bd3 d5 5. c3 Qc7 6. O-O Bg7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. Nbd2 Nh5 11. g3 Bg4 12. Be2 Rab8 13. Re1 Rbd8 14. Nf1 Nf6 15. Ne3 Bc8 16. Bf1 Ng4 17. Qe2 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Rfe8 19. Bg2 b5 $2 ({White has markedly improved his position and now plans Rad1 or Rac1 and then c4, with advantage. Black should now continue with} 19... Bg4 20. Rac1 Bxf3 21. Bxf3 Qb6 {, when he has surrendered the bishop pair but in return he exerts strong pressure on the white d4-pawn, preventing the c4 advance. His choice to weaken the queenside is not to be recommended.}) {Starting a ‘suspicious’ minority attack, as Black is not quite ready for it...} 20. Ba3 $1 {White adapts his plans. Placing the bishop on c5 and then advancing his pawns on the queenside will secure him an advantage.} Bf5 ({After} 20... e5 21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. Nd4 $1 {, White is better.}) 21. Bc5 Be4 22. a4 $1 Rb8 $6 ({Black had to play} 22... bxa4 23. Rxa4 a5 {, with some advantage for White.}) ({Instead,} 22... a6 23. axb5 axb5 24. b4 {would signify a standard failure of the minority attack.}) 23. axb5 Rxb5 24. Bf1 $2 (24. b4 $1 Qd7 25. Bf1 Rb7 26. Ra6 $16 {would be just great.}) 24... Rxb3 $1 ({Black faces difficulties after} 24... Rb7 25. Nd2 Bf5 26. b4 $1 {, as the pressure on the weak a7-pawn is terrible.}) 25. Nd2 Rb2 $6 (25... Rbb8 26. Nxe4 dxe4 27. Qxe4 a5 $16 {could be a better idea.}) 26. Nxe4 dxe4 27. Qxe4 {White has an obvious advantage due to his better pawn structure and the bishop pair.} e6 $6 (27... Na5 28. Rab1 Rxb1 29. Rxb1 e6 30. Qc2 $16 {was more or less forced.}) 28. Bg2 $2 (28. Ra6 Rc8 29. Bg2 {would be curtains.}) 28... Na5 $1 29. Re2 $1 Rxe2 ({The exchange of Black's only active piece determines the outcome of the game, as then Black cannot hope for any counterplay. The exchange is compulsory (} 29... Rbb8 {) .}) 30. Qxe2 Rb8 31. Bf3 $6 ({The direct} 31. Qa6 $2 Nb3 32. Qxa7 Qxa7 33. Bxa7 Rc8 {gives Black chances,}) ({but White could have opted for} 31. Ra4 Rb1+ 32. Bf1 Rb7 33. Qa6 Nb3 34. Bd6 Qd7 35. Bf4 $16 {. Mutual time-trouble interferes with the logical flow of the game.}) 31... h5 32. h4 Nc6 $2 ({Black's only defensive chance lay in the exchange of dark squared bishops with} 32... Bf8 $1 33. Bxf8 Rxf8 {( 33...Kxf8 34.Qa6 ( 34.c4 $14 ) 34...Qxc3? ( 34...Nc4 $13 ) 35.Qd6+ ( 35.Rxa5? Rb1+! ( 35...Qxf3? 36.Qd6++- ) 36.Kg2 Qe1 37.Kh3 Qxf2= ) 35...Kg7 36.Qe5+ Kh7 37.Rxa5+- )} 34. Ra3 Nc4 35. Ra6 $1 {, when White retains an advantage, but one smaller than in comparison with the position after his 30th move.}) 33. Ra6 $1 Ne5 34. Rxa7 Qc8 35. Bd6 Rb1+ 36. Kg2 Qxc3 ({Desperation, as} 36... Nxf3 37. Qxf3 {, threatening 38.Qxf7+ or 38.Ra8, would also win for White.}) 37. Bxe5 Rb2 38. Rc7 $1 Qa3 {Black lost on time in a hopeless position.} 1-0

