1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Nh5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nge2 Nb6 11. O-O g6 12. Na4 $1 {Black's knight on b6 was making a minority attack (b4-b5) difficult because of its potential to occupy the c4-square. So White exchanges it off.} Nxa4 13. Qxa4 O-O 14. b4 {Starting the minority attack. Black's next move holds it up for a while, but in the long run it's very difficult for him to stop b4-b5.} a6 15. Qb3 ({A nice trap is revealed after} 15. b5 $2 cxb5 16. Bxb5 Bf5 {and the white bishop is lost!}) 15... Be6 16. a4 Rfc8 17. Qb2 Ng7 18. b5 {And now the minority attack breaks through. Whatever Black does he will end up with some pawn weaknesses; for example, capturing on b5 with his c-pawn leaves the d5-pawn weak. In the game he opts for contracting a weak c6-pawn.} axb5 19. axb5 Bf5 ({Black should have tried} 19... c5 {, when} 20. dxc5 Qxc5 {, leaves a great square for White's knight on d4, but this should not be the end of the world.}) 20. Nf4 Bxd3 21. Nxd3 Nf5 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. bxc6 bxc6 {White has succeeded to ideally perform a typical minority attack. Black remained with a backward weak c-pawn and no real counterplay but of course he can defend it. His main problem is that he will remain under pressure and on the defence for a long time, thus blundering possibilities are increased. Also, it must be noted that White can combine initiative on every part of the board, using the 'two weaknesses rule' to the maximum effect.} 24. Rc1 Nh4 $5 25. Qe2 $1 (25. Rxc6 $6 Nxg2 26. Kxg2 Qe4+ 27. Kg3 Qxd3 {gives Black counterplay.}) 25... Ra3 26. g3 ({Here} 26. Rxc6 $6 {is answered by} Qe4 {26...Nxg2 27.Kxg2 Qe4+ 28.Qf3 Rxd3=} 27. Ne1 Ra1 28. f3 Nxf3+ $1 29. gxf3 Qh4 30. Kf1 Qh3+ 31. Kg1 Qh4 {.}) 26... Qe4 27. Ne1 Nf5 28. Qc2 $1 {The exchange of queens kills Black's counterplay. Torture time!} Qxc2 29. Rxc2 Ne7 30. Kf1 $6 (30. g4 $1 {here or on the next move, would be the proper white plan.}) 30... f6 $6 (30... h5 $1 {would have been a good idea so that White's g4 advance would not leave Black with a weak h-pawn.}) 31. Ke2 $6 Kf7 $6 (31... h5 $1 {was still the right idea.}) 32. Nd3 $6 Ke6 $6 33. Rb2 $6 Ra7 $6 (33... h5 $1 {, is still correct, and this was the last chance.}) 34. g4 $1 {Fixing Black's h-pawn as a target.} g5 35. Rb8 Kf7 36. Rh8 Kg7 (36... Kg6 37. h3 Rc7 38. Kd2 Rc8 39. Rxc8 Nxc8 40. Kc3 {would see White's king heading for c5 with the pressure going into the knight endgame.}) 37. Rd8 Rc7 (37... Kg6 38. Rd6 {prevents an eventual ...h5.}) 38. Nc5 Kf7 39. Kf3 Ng6 40. Kg3 Ra7 41. Rd6 Rc7 {Difficult to find some proper defensive ideas for Black… The passivity of the black pieces and the created targets, are just a pleasure for the white forces!} ({Note that} 41... Ne7 $6 42. Nd7 Ng8 43. Nb8 {wins material.}) 42. Na6 Rc8 43. Rd7+ Ne7 44. Nc5 Ra8 45. Rd6 Ra1 {Seeing that White is ready to play h4 and maybe f3 and e4, Black decides that passive defence is doomed to failure.} 46. Nd7 $1 f5 47. Ne5+ Kg7 48. h3 $1 fxg4 49. hxg4 Rc1 ({Or} 49... Ra6 50. Re6 Kf8 51. Nf3 {.}) 50. Re6 Ng6 (50... Kf8 51. Nf3 {again wins the g-pawn.}) 51. Rxc6 Rxc6 52. Nxc6 {White is now a pawn up with the d5-pawn being very weak as well. He does a neat job of winning the endgame.} Kf6 53. f3 Ke6 54. Nb4 Kd6 55. Kf2 Nf8 56. e4 dxe4 57. fxe4 Ne6 58. e5+ Kd7 59. Ke3 Nf4 60. Nd3 Nd5+ 61. Ke4 Kc6 62. Nf2 Nf4 63. Nd1 h5 64. gxh5 Nxh5 65. Ne3 Nf4 66. Ng4 Ne2 67. Nf6 Ng3+ 68. Kf3 Nf5 69. d5+ Kc5 70. Kg4 Nh6+ 71. Kxg5 Nf7+ 72. Kf4 Kd4 73. e6 Nd6 74. e7 1-0

