1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9. Nf3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. Bxf6 {With this and his next move, White gets his minority attack going straight away.} ({Another way to play for b4 is} 11. Rab1 {.}) 11... Bxf6 12. b4 Bg4 13. Nd2 Rc8 ({A more flexible continuation was seen in the game Timman-Kasparov, London 1984:} 13... Be7 $1 14. Rab1 Bd6 15. Bf5 Bh5 $1 16. Rfc1 g6 17. Bd3 Qg5 18. Ne2 Nd7 19. h3 a6 20. a4 Rac8 21. Nf1 Bxe2 22. Bxe2 Qe7 23. Qb3 Nf6 {½-½.}) 14. Bf5 $1 {Disarming Black of his bishop pair cannot be a bad choice!} Bxf5 15. Qxf5 g6 {In some ways Black would prefer not to go for this, because one day he might like to get a rook to g6 or h6, seeking counterchances.} ({The other usual continuation is} 15... Qd7 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 17. a4 Be7 18. Rfb1 $14 {, as was seen in Korchnoi-Karpov, Baguio City 1978. White keeps a small but pleasant plus, as he is the only one with a dangerous plan in mind; the minority attack! By the way, V.Korchnoi won that game!}) ({Finally, Black's other option must be noted:} 15... Be7 16. Rab1 a6 17. Rfc1 Bd6 18. a4 g6 19. Qd3 f5 20. g3 $14 {½-½ Zilberman-Bagirov, Frunze 1983. Of course, White could continue without any real danger; something that it is a luxury in modern chess, where threats are luring around, in nearly every move!}) 16. Qd3 Qd6 17. Rfb1 Bg7 18. a4 Nd7 19. Ra2 $1 ({White can't play} 19. b5 $2 {straightaway because of} c5 $1 20. dxc5 $2 Nxc5 {.}) 19... Re6 20. Rc2 Rce8 21. Nb3 Nf6 ({Perhaps Black would have had better chances of counterplay had he played} 21... f5 $5 {, trying to lever open the e-file. This too is a minority attack, trying to extend control of the half open e-file with a pawn lever. White should answer it with} 22. g3 {.}) 22. h3 b6 $6 ({After} 22... a6 23. b5 axb5 24. axb5 Ra8 25. Nc5 Re7 26. bxc6 bxc6 27. Rcb2 {, Black would suffer and be tortured for a long, long time. Maybe computers would be able to keep the draw but a human being is unable to! Nevertheless, this was Black's best defensive set-up.}) 23. Nc1 (23. b5 $2 c5 $1 {would again play into Black's hands.}) 23... Bh6 24. N1e2 Nh5 $6 {Allowing the undesirable breakthrough.} ({Something like} 24... Bg5 {would leave White with the task of making the b5 advance effective.}) 25. b5 $1 {This was a long time in coming, but it's very strong. White is breaking through on the c-file and the d5-pawn becomes very weak.} Qd7 ({The side-lined h5-knight doesn't allow Black to continue with the desirable (but unplayable now)} 25... c5 $2 26. dxc5 bxc5 27. Nxd5 {.}) 26. bxc6 Rxc6 27. Qb5 Rec8 $2 {A blunder.} (27... Qe6 $16 {was Black's only chance.}) 28. Rbc1 $2 {Which White did not notice!} (28. Nxd5 {would win on the spot.}) 28... R8c7 $2 (28... Qe6 {would have been better, unpinning the rook and introducing the possibility of a sacrifice on e3. White then could continue with} 29. a5 Nf6 30. axb6 axb6 31. Qb3 $16 {, with play against two weak black pawns.}) 29. g4 $1 a6 ({Both} 29... Nf6 {and 29...Ng7 are answered by} 30. Nxd5 {.}) 30. Qxa6 Nf6 31. Nxd5 $1 Nxg4 ({If} 31... Nxd5 {, there follows} 32. Rxc6 Rxc6 33. Qa8+) ({and} 31... Qxd5 {is met by} 32. Rxc6 Rxc6 33. Qa8+ {, too.}) 32. Rxc6 Qxd5 33. Qa8+ {Black resigned due to 33...Kg7 34.Rxg6+ .} 1-0

