[PlyCount "73"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} f5 2. Bg5 Nf6 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 c6 5. Nd2 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. Qf3 g6 8. a3 Be6 9. h3 Qe7 10. Ne2 Nd7 11. Nf4 Bf7 {Both sides have developed harmoniously, without coming into direct contact or troubling one another. White correctly decides on the c4 advance, as this represents his most dangerous plan in practice. Later on, he can adopt a type of minority attack on the queenside, directed against the black c6-pawn. Naturally, Black's position is fully satisfactory and he can develop his own plans in the centre and on the kingside.} 12. c4 $1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 O-O 14. O-O Nb6 15. Bxf7+ Rxf7 16. Rac1 Re8 17. Rc2 Qd8 $6 {Black should have taken the chance to exchange his darksquared bishop for the white knight. In that case the chances would be even.} 18. Rb1 a6 19. Nd3 $1 Bb8 20. b4 $1 {White is better due to his better pawn structure and the availability of a concrete plan (minority attack against c6). In contrast, Black's kingside attack is essentially a dream. Black failed to appreciate this during the game and, as a result, quickly ended-up in a lost position.} Rfe7 21. g3 Kg7 22. Nc5 h5 23. h4 $1 Nd5 {Totally pointless.} ({Black should have opted for} 23... Qd5 {, so as, after a queen exchange, to advance his kingside pawns, trying to counterbalance White's queenside advance. Throughout the entire game, Black's passive treatment of his problems allowed White to freely proceed with his plans.}) 24. Nf1 $1 {A prophylactic move, preventing any sacrificial idea on e3.} Qc8 25. a4 Kh6 $2 {After this, Black ends in troubles.} ({The typical} 25... b5 $1 {was his best chance.}) 26. b5 $1 {White has completed his plan while Black is still in search of play.} axb5 27. axb5 g5 $2 {Black's game was positionally very difficult, but this move hastens the end.} 28. hxg5+ fxg5 29. Nxb7 $1 {White's great positional superiority gives rise to tactical combinations!} g4 30. Qg2 Qxb7 31. Rxc6+ Kg7 32. Qxd5 {White has won material while retaining his positional plusses. Black could have resigned here with a clear conscience, but prolonged the game due to the mutual time pressure.} Rf7 33. Ra1 h4 34. Raa6 hxg3 35. Nxg3 Bxg3 36. fxg3 Qe7 37. Re6 1-0

