1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 a5 11. Nc3 Na6 12. Rfe1 Nb4 13. Rac1 Nfd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qb3 b6 16. Ne5 Bb7 17. Nd3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Bd6 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 {White's plan is pressure on the queenside via the semi-open c-file. At the same time, utilising some tactics, he will advance his pawns on that flank, effecting a minority attack.} 20. Rc2 $1 f5 {Black wishes to protect his backward c7-pawn via his second rank and is thus compelled to advance his f-pawn, so as to create the necessary space for piece manoeuvring. However, this creates additional weaknesses.} 21. Rec1 Rf7 22. Qb5 $1 {Threatening 23.Rc6! Bxc6 24.Rxc6 Qd7 25.Bxd5 .} Rd8 $6 ({Black had to play} 22... Kh8 {, or}) (22... Rd7 {, to prevent White's aforementioned threat. The text has similar aims, but leaves the queenside undefended. White immediately exploits this fact in the best possible manner.}) 23. b4 $1 axb4 ({Black loses after} 23... Qxb4 24. Qxb4 axb4 25. Rxc7 Rxc7 26. Rxc7 Ba8 27. Rc2 $1 {and 28.Rb2.}) 24. a5 $1 {The only move but also very strong, as it breaks up Black's queenside.} (24. Rb2 $2 Ra8 $1 {allows Black to breathe freely and is pointless.}) 24... Ra8 25. axb6 c6 $2 ({Black tries to complicate the position as} 25... Qxb6 26. Rc5 $1 Re7 27. e3 Qxb5 {27...b3 28.Qxb6 cxb6 29.Rb5+-} 28. Rxb5 c6 29. Rxb4 $14 {is clearly advantageous for White. Still, he should have opted for this line.}) 26. Qc5 $2 ({Completely unacceptable, as White had the excellent} 26. Rxc6 $1 Bxc6 27. Rxc6 Ra1+ 28. Bf1 Qd7 29. Qc5 $1 {, winning.}) 26... Qxc5 27. dxc5 Rff8 28. Bxd5+ $2 {A wrong idea, based on a miscalculation…} ({White should have continued with the simple} 28. Rb1 $1 Ra4 29. Bxd5+ {29.e3! Kf7 30.Rcb2 Ra5 31.Rc1 Ra4 32.Bf3 $16} cxd5 30. c6 b3 $1 {30...Ba6? 31.b7 Kf7 32.Rcb2+- , or 30...Rb8? 31.cxb7 Rxb7 32.Rc8+ Kf7 33.Rc7+ Rxc7 34.bxc7 Ra8 35.Rxb4 $16} 31. Rcc1 {31.Rxb3? Rc4 $17} Bxc6 32. Rxc6 Rb4 33. Rc3 b2 34. Rc2 Rxb6 35. Rbxb2 Rxb2 36. Rxb2 {, with a slight edge.}) 28... cxd5 29. c6 Rab8 $1 {This simple move escaped White's attention when he sacrificed on d5.} ({After} 29... Ba6 $6 30. b7 Rab8 $1 {30...Rae8? 31.Rb1+-} 31. c7 Bc4 32. c8=Q Rfxc8 33. bxc8=Q+ Rxc8 34. Rb2 Rb8 35. Ra1 $14 {, White should feel pleased,}) ({but} 29... Ra6 30. cxb7 Rxb6 31. Rc7 b3 32. Kg2 $14 {is also possible.}) 30. cxb7 Rxb7 31. Rc6 Rfb8 $1 {White lacks the necessary tempo to win the black b4-pawn for free and thus he is forced to compromise with just a draw by repetition.} 32. Rc8+ Kf7 33. R8c7+ Ke6 ({White has a slight advantage in the ending resulting from} 33... Rxc7 34. bxc7 Rc8 35. Rb1 Rxc7 36. Rxb4 {, although the game would almost surely end in a draw anyway. So, the text is more or less correct, although it was played with a very wrong idea in mind…}) 34. R7c6+ Ke5 $2 ({In time-trouble Black plays for a win, avoiding a repetition with} 34... Kf7 {. However, this is a mistake as the black king is caught in an unusual mating net, which was very hard to foresee.}) 35. f4+ $1 Ke4 36. Re6+ Kd4 37. Kf2 $1 Rxb6 38. Re3 $1 {An unusual position where the black king, despite the reduced material, is trapped in the centre of the board. White threatens 39.Rd3+ Ke4 40.Rcd1 and 41.Rd4#, (or 39.Kf3) .} g5 39. Rd3+ Ke4 40. Re3+ Kd4 {White made some move repetitions in order to reach the time control (on the 40th move). From a practical viewpoint this practice is definitely indicated, as it allows a detailed examination of the position without the burden of time pressure. Even if we are certain of what to play, there is no harm in gaining some time to verify the variations we have calculated.} 41. Kf3 ({This still wins, but simpler was} 41. Rd3+ Ke4 42. Rcd1 gxf4 43. Rxd5 $1 fxg3+ 44. hxg3 {and 45.R1d4#, as indicated during the post mortem by GM Nikolaidis.}) 41... g4+ 42. Kf2 Rh6 ({There is no salvation, because Black's only other option,} 42... Rd6 {, leads to decisive material losses:} 43. Rc7 $1 {43.Rd3+ Ke4 44.Rcd1? d4!} Rbb6 {43...b3 44.Rd3+ Ke4 45.Re7++-} 44. Rd3+ Ke4 45. Re7+ Re6 46. Rxe6+ Rxe6 47. Re3+ {.}) 43. h4 $1 {Black either gets mated or loses a rook, as in the previous note.} 1-0

