{The next game was a painful defeat for the FIDE World Champion Anatoly Karpov, one of the strongest positional players and greatest defenders of all time. Missing a strong tactical shot is quite usual and it shouldn’t surprise us; after all, tactics are part of the game! Simply, in top-games they do not occur so often… And this happens because top-players can see and defend against them!} 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Nf3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 Be6 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. a3 Qe7 (14... a5 $5 {is interesting:} 15. Na4 N6d7 16. Nc5 b6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. e4 c5 $13 {.}) 15. b4 Rac8 16. Rfc1 ({Black was ready to answer} 16. b5 $2 {, with} cxb5 $1 17. Bxb5 Ne4 $17 {.}) 16... N6d7 17. Ne2 $1 {White is in no hurry and before he goes for b5, regroups his pieces.} Ng6 (17... Qd8 $6 {is too passive:} 18. Nf4 {18.Ng3 a5 19.Qd2 $14} Ng6 19. Nxe6 Rxe6 20. Bf5 Rd6 21. Ne5 $16 {.}) 18. Ng3 Ndf8 (18... b6 $6 {can only weaken Black's queenside:} 19. Qa4 {19.Ba6 Rc7 20.Rab1 $14} Nb8 20. Rc3 $16 {.}) 19. Nd2 Nh4 20. Nb3 Qg5 {Black starts his usual operations on the opposite side; the kingside.} 21. Kh2 Rc7 22. Nc5 Bc8 23. Re1 g6 ({Black could also think about} 23... f5 $5 24. f4 Qf6 25. a4 $14 {.}) 24. Rac1 h5 25. b5 $2 {The wrong moment to carry on this thematic advance.} ({White should insert} 25. f4 $1 Qf6 26. Qf2 $14 {.}) 25... Nxg2 $1 {A nice but not too difficult combination.} 26. Kxg2 (26. Rg1 $6 Nxe3 $1 {26...Nh4 $17} 27. fxe3 Rxe3 $17 {can only be beneficial for Black.}) 26... h4 27. bxc6 hxg3 $1 ({There was no need to delay the piece recapture with} 27... bxc6 $2 28. e4 Ne6 29. exd5 Nf4+ 30. Kh2 Rxe1 31. Rxe1 cxd5 $13 {.}) 28. fxg3 Rxe3 29. Rxe3 $6 ({White regains his pawn after} 29. Qf2 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Rxc6 31. Re5 {, but Black keeps a firm grip after} Qd8 $17 {. Netherless, White should have gone for this.}) 29... Qxe3 30. cxb7 Bxb7 31. Qc3 $2 {A blunder in a difficult position.} ({White could not be saved with} 31. Qb2 $6 Ne6 $1 {31...Bc8? 32.Rd1 $13} 32. Bf1 Nxd4 {either, but he should have tried.}) (31. Rb1 $1 Bc8 {31...Qxd4?! 32.Rxb7 Rxc5 33.Qf2 Qxf2+ 34.Kxf2 $15} 32. Qf2 {32.Rb4?! a5! 33.Ra4 Bd7 34.Rxa5 Qxd4-+} Bxh3+ 33. Kg1 Qg5 $17 {.}) 31... Rxc5 $1 32. Qxc5 (32. dxc5 $2 d4+ {.}) 32... Qxd3 {Two pieces for a rook and a weak white king is no match for White...} 33. Qc3 Qe2+ 34. Kg1 Ne6 35. Re1 Nxd4 $1 36. Kh1 Nb5 0-1

