[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

{Not every time do we have to face a 'QGD' opening in the given examples; remember that minority attacks can occur in any opening, for example the 'Caro-Kann'. The next two games are good examples of this opening, which, of course, is very similar to ‘QGD’, ‘Carlsbad Pawn Structure’. Keep an open mind and react according to the pawn structures!} 1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 e6 10. Nf3 Qb6 11. a4 Rc8 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 h6 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. h3 Bd6 17. O-O Kf8 18. f4 $1 {White starts operations on the kingside, in this reversed 'QGD' pawn structure.} Be8 (18... Nxe5 $2 {does (not) win a pawn but loses a piece after} 19. fxe5 Bxe5 {, when the simple} 20. a5 {decides.}) 19. Bf2 $1 Qc7 (19... g6 $6 {doesn't avoid White's 'annoying' advance:} 20. f5 $1 gxf5 21. Bxf5 exf5 22. Qxf5 Qd8 23. Bh4 {.}) 20. Bh4 Ng8 21. f5 $1 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Bxe5 ({Or} 22... Bc5+ 23. Kh1 exf5 24. Bxf5 Ra8 25. e6 $16 {.}) 23. fxe6 Bf6 24. exf7 Bxf7 25. Nf3 $1 Bxh4 ({What else? After} 25... g5 26. Bf2 Kg7 27. Bd4 {, White is near to winning.}) 26. Nxh4 Nf6 27. Ng6+ Bxg6 28. Bxg6 {The smoke has been cleared and White has a nearly decisive advantage, due to Black's un-coordinated pieces - the rook on h8 still hasn't come into play...} Ke7 $1 {Probably Black's best, as it is essential to connect his rooks and transfer his king to a more secure place, if there is any left...} 29. Qf5 Kd8 $6 ({Good or bad, Black was forced to go for} 29... Rhd8 30. Rae1+ Kf8 31. Bh7 $16 {and pray.}) 30. Rae1 Qc5+ 31. Kh1 Rf8 {Black is in a difficult situation and without a good move.} ({Other options such as} 31... Rc6 32. Bf7 Kc7 {32...Rf8 33.Bxd5+-} 33. Qg6 {also fail to impress.}) 32. Qe5 $1 Rc7 ({No good replies for Black anymore, as neither} 32... Qc7 33. Qxd5+ Nxd5 34. Rxf8+ Kd7 35. Bf5+ Kd6 36. Rxc8 Qf7 37. Re6+ {,}) ({nor} 32... a5 33. c4 $1 d4 34. Qg3 {hold. Not a surprise, due to the central location of the black king!}) 33. b4 $1 Qc6 (33... Qxc3 34. Qd6+ {.}) 34. c4 $1 dxc4 35. Bf5 Rff7 36. Rd1+ Rfd7 (36... Nd7 37. Rfe1 {.}) 37. Bxd7 Rxd7 (37... Nxd7 38. Rf8# {.}) 38. Qb8+ Ke7 (38... Qc8 39. Rxd7+ Nxd7 40. Qd6 {.}) 39. Rde1+ {Black resigned as mate follows: 39...Kf7 40.Qe8 . A great attacking game by the great R.J.Fischer!} 1-0

