1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Bc4 c6 5. O-O d5 6. exd5 cxd5 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. c3 Nc6 9. Nbd2 Nf6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 O-O 12. Re1 e6 {A reversed 'QGD' pawn structure. Here White should try to attack on the kingside, using the semi-open e-file as a route to deliver his major pieces there, while Black should aim to exercise the minority attack after an eventual ...b5-b4. Yet, both of these plans are much easier to describe than to implement here - Black's kingside is well-fortified, while the minority attack is not on the menu yet. Such positions require great patience and careful assessment of any committal move.} 13. Bg5 Qe7 14. Qd2 a6 15. Bf4 (15. a4 {would allow Black to feel alive by placing his knights on the edge of the board!:} Na5 16. Qf4 Nh5 $13 {.}) 15... Qd8 16. Bg5 Qc7 17. Bh6 Rfe8 18. Re2 {A correct plan: doubling rooks on the semi-open file is a logical follow-up.} Bxh6 19. Qxh6 Qe7 ({Maybe Black should go for a slightly worse endgame, exchanging some pieces with} 19... e5 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Rae1 Rae8 23. Rxe5 Rxe5 24. Qd2 $14 {.}) 20. Rae1 Rac8 21. Re3 Qf8 22. Qh4 Qg7 23. Ng5 h6 $6 ({Black could disregard the g5-knight for a while and start preparing his own play by} 23... b5 {- the variation} 24. Rf3 h6 25. Qf4 hxg5 26. Qxf6 Qxf6 27. Rxf6 Kg7 {is quite OK for him.}) 24. Nf3 g5 $6 {Black is neglecting the good old rule - not to advance pawns in an area where he is weaker. This move may look active, but it weakens Black's position considerably, while not bringing any definite benefits. Note that White's bishop, only two moves ago limited by Black's pawn chain on the kingside, is potentially very dangerous now.} 25. Qg3 Nh5 26. Qh2 Kh8 27. h4 $1 g4 28. Ne5 Rg8 (28... Nxe5 {would have led to a similar position after} 29. Rxe5 Nf6 30. Qf4 $16 {.}) 29. Nxc6 Rxc6 30. g3 $1 {Self-prisoning the white queen is not logical but White has calculated that soon he will be able to offer her a better future!} Rb6 31. R1e2 Nf6 32. Qg2 Rd6 33. Qf1 Nd7 34. Qd1 Nf8 35. Qb3 Rd7 36. Qb6 {Who could believe that the white queen would move so quickly from h2 to b6?} Qf6 37. Qb3 Rc7 38. Re1 Re7 39. Qd1 {Back to base again! The black kingside is the real target!} Qg7 $6 ({Black should not allow the white rook to enter e5, so he should have opted for} 39... Nd7 40. a4 Qg7 41. a5 $16 {.}) 40. Re5 $1 Qf6 41. Qd2 Rc7 42. Rf1 ({White could win a pawn by playing} 42. Rh5 $1 Kg7 43. Qe2 {, but the text move is good too.}) 42... Nd7 43. Rh5 Kg7 44. f3 $1 {Opening the f-file spells disaster for Black.} Kf8 (44... gxf3 45. Rxf3 {.}) 45. Rxh6 Qe7 46. fxg4 {An 'easy' game without too many variations, but just typical plans and manoeuvres. Black was very late in his own plans on the queenside and in the end he suffered a painful lose.} 1-0

