{When the side with the ‘obligation’ to execute a minority attack fails to comply, then things can turn into nightmare. Well, nothing new under the sun, as activity and planned operation are just a necessity and not a luxury…} 1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 a6 4. Nc3 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. d4 Be7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O c6 9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. Rc1 Re8 {Black has developed comfortably while, on the other hand, White has failed to contest the initiative arising from the benefit of moving first. Instead of the colourless 10.Rc1?!, White should have tried 10.Rb1, planning a minority attack by b4-b5. That is, after all, White's only suitable plan in such pawn structures.} 11. Ne5 Bf8 12. Qb3 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd7 14. Bf4 Nb6 $1 {Preventing 15.Na4 and planning to regroup the knight with ...Nc4-d6.} 15. Bg5 $6 ({In such cases, staying with an isolated pawn is mostly a must:} 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Be6 17. Qd3 h6 $15 {.}) 15... Qxg5 $1 16. Qxb6 Rb8 {Black now has the bishop pair and attacking chances on the kingside. By comparison, White is too late with his plan, the minority attack.} 17. e3 h5 $1 18. h4 $2 ({Although this move seems to halt Black's attack, in fact it only creates weaknesses around the white king. The immediate} 18. b4 {is better.}) 18... Qe7 19. Ne2 Bg4 20. Nf4 g5 $1 21. hxg5 Qxg5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gh5h4,Gf8d6] White 'refused' to adopt the standard minority attack plan on the queenside and has therefore failed to react to Black's kingside initiative. His position is inferior and under fire from Black's pieces. This is a good example of punishment for the side that doesn't achieve any plans, a concept of great significance in modern chess.} 22. Qb3 Bd6 23. Rfe1 h4 $1 {The negative aspects of 18.h4? are constantly highlighted.} 24. gxh4 Qxh4 25. Nd3 Qh2+ 26. Kf1 Re6 $1 {Black's attack now crashes through.} 27. f3 Rf6 28. f4 Rg6 29. Rc2 Bh3 $1 {And as White is losing the house, he decided to call it a day…} 0-1

