[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 c6 4. b3 Nd7 5. Bb2 f5 6. Qc2 Ndf6 7. Be2 Bd6 8. d3 Qe7 9. Be5 Nh6 10. O-O Nf7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Rac1 Bd7 14. d4 Kh8 15. Rfd1 Ne4 16. Ne1 Nfg5 17. Nd3 Rf6 18. f4 Nf7 19. Ne5 Qe7 20. Rf1 Rc8 21. Bd3 Nxc3 22. Qxc3 Nxe5 23. fxe5 Rff8 {White has the more active bishop, as his central pawns are placed on the opposite colour of his minor piece. Of course, having an advantage doesn't guarantee a win without hard work and inspiration! White has to form a plan and execute it with accuracy. As the centre is fixed and the kingside doesn't offer that much, the place to operate is the queenside, so White must make his plans on this side of the board.} 24. b4 $1 g5 {A natural reaction. Black's main counterplay lies in the ...f4 advance, which will weaken the d4-pawn, turning it to a target.} 25. Qd2 $1 {No hurry! White keeps this advance (...f4) in reserve.} Rf7 {Planning ...Rcf8 and...f4. Although it is hard to say if this was the correct follow-up by Black, the text allows White to change the pawn structure in his favour and achieve a potential minority attack. In other words, to obtain a clear and effective plan for the future…} 26. cxd5 $1 exd5 {A committal decision, giving White a protected passed pawn.} ({The other option was} 26... cxd5 27. Rxc8+ Bxc8 28. Rc1 $16 {and was also quite unpleasant for Black.}) 27. Rf2 Rcf8 28. Rcf1 Be6 29. g3 {As mentioned, it is essential to prevent any possible counterplay by Black involving ...f4, so prophylaxis against it is a good way to proceed.} Kg7 30. a3 h6 31. Qc2 Qd7 {White has an obvious advantage, based on concrete factors: protected passed pawn (the result of the transformation of a strong outpost), the better bishop and queenside initiative. Black cannot interfere with White's plan and therefore fails to put up strong resistance.} 32. a4 $1 a6 33. b5 axb5 34. axb5 h5 $6 {A desperate attempt at counterplay, ultimately succeeding only in weakening the dark squares around the black king. Although it was tough for Black to accept the passivity of his position, he should have just waited, hoping for mistakes on White's part.} ({By the way,} 34... cxb5 $6 35. Qb1 $1 {would not help: the pawns on b7 and d5 are very weak.}) 35. bxc6 bxc6 36. Rc1 Rc8 37. Qd1 $1 Kh6 38. Be2 $1 {Expecting 38...g4 (which puts an end to any hopes Black might have had to confuse the issue with ...f4) 39.Bd3!, intending Qa4 and Rfc2. Black, not willing to acquiesce to the inevitable, decides to commit suicide instead.} h4 $2 39. gxh4 gxh4 40. Rf4 $1 Rg7+ 41. Kh1 Rg6 42. Qe1 $1 Kg7 43. Qxh4 c5 44. Rg1 $1 {An attack on the exposed black king is the fastest route to victory.} Rxg1+ 45. Kxg1 Rg8 46. Qf6+ Kh7+ 47. Kf2 Rg7 48. Rh4+ Kg8 49. Rh6 $1 {Remarkably, the e6-bishop is lost!} 1-0

