{What move should Black consider to avoid placing a pawn on c6 and prevent White from gaining an advantage with an immediate b5 advance?} 15... Re7 $1 {[%mdl 32768] Black avoids placing his pawn on c6 so as not to give a target for an immediate b5 advance. This idea is often met and, as it is of great importance, must always be taken into account.} *

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 1: Pawn "]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.05.28"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.2) Other Side/^s Initiative"]
[Black "Grivas, Efstratios vs. Skal"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "E10"]
[PlyCount "89"]
[EventDate "2024.??.??"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Qb3 Qd6 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. b4 $1 Bf5 12. e3 Nd7 13. Be2 Nf6 14. O-O Rfe8 15. Rfc1 Re7 $1 {Black avoids placing his pawn on c6 so as not to give a target for an immediate b5 advance. This idea is often met and, as it is of great importance, must always be taken into account.} 16. Qc5 $1 Qe6 $6 {Black believes that he can pursue aggressive intentions on the kingside and thus avoids the exchange of queens.} ({However, as this concept is not really feasible, it is better to play} 16... Ne4 $1 17. Qxd6 cxd6 $1 {, with only a minimal advantage for White.}) 17. Nd2 g5 $6 {Black's aggression is wishful thinking.} ({Fortifying his defence with} 17... a6 $1 {is more helpful.}) 18. b5 h5 19. a4 $1 Kg7 ({White also retains the advantage after} 19... h4 20. a5 h3 21. a6 $1 b6 22. Qc6 $16 {.}) 20. a5 b6 21. Qc6 $1 Rc8 22. axb6 cxb6 {Black could not avoid the creation of a backward pawn, either on a7 or on c7. He opted for the one on a7, judging that possession of the a-file (after 22...axb6) would be even more favourable for White.} 23. Qxe6 Bxe6 24. Rxc8 Bxc8 25. Rc1 Bb7 26. Nf3 $1 g4 $6 (26... Ne4 27. Ne5 f6 $1 {is a better try, although} 28. Nd3 $1 {preserves an advantage for White, , but not 28.Nc6? Rc7 29.Bxh5 a6! .}) 27. Nh4 $1 Kf8 {White has a significant advantage, as he has successfully completed his minority attack (the white pawn on b5 is worth as much as a7 and b6 together), controls the c-file, enjoys a better pawn structure (two pawn islands versus three, isolated black pawn on d5, weakened black kingside) and more active pieces. The problem that almost always appears in this type of position is that the side with the advantage is unable to improve its position further or immediately exploit its superiority on the flank where this superiority exists. The solution is simple and consists of 'exploiting' the other parts of the board as well (centre and kingside) as the opponent's pieces are tied up with the protection of the queenside, where direct pressure is applied, and will not be able to defend properly.} 28. h3 $1 {Threatening 29.hxg4 hxg4 30.Kh2, followed by 31.Nf5 and Nh6.} g3 ({Black's choice is not pleasant, because after} 28... gxh3 29. gxh3 {followed by Nf5-g3, he would also lose material.}) 29. Nf5 $1 gxf2+ 30. Kxf2 Rd7 31. Ng3 Ke7 (31... h4 32. Nf5 {is similar. White finally converts his positional superiority into material gain.}) 32. Nxh5 Ne4+ 33. Ke1 f5 34. Bd3 Nd6 35. g4 $1 fxg4 36. hxg4 Kf8 37. g5 Re7 38. Kd2 Bc8 39. Rc6 Re6 40. g6 Bd7 41. Rc7 Be8 42. Nf4 Rf6 43. Nxd5 Rf2+ 44. Ke1 Rg2 45. Nf4 1-0

