1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Rc1 Nbd7 7. Nf3 c6 8. Qc2 Re8 9. a3 a6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 Nf8 12. O-O g6 {This idea was first introduced in 1930 by Fritz Saemisch. Black's plan is simple: ...Ne6-g7 and ...Bf5, exchanging light-squared bishops. But it is true that Black loses valuable time and he gets nearly no activity.} 13. Na4 (13. Rfe1 $5 Ne6 14. Bh4 Ng7 15. Qb3 Nfh5 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. e4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 $14 {, was seen in Le Roux-Legky, France 2005.}) ({Also,} 13. b4 Ne6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. a4 Ng7 16. b5 axb5 17. axb5 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. Na4 $14 {should be taken into account, as in Kotov-Pachman, Venice 1950.}) 13... Ne6 14. Bh4 Ng7 15. Nc5 Nd7 $1 {Exchanges help the 'weaker' side!} 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. b4 Nb6 {Preparing the occupation of the c4-square, after the light-squared bishops' exchange. White must hurry.} 18. a4 $1 Bf5 19. Nd2 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Nf5 21. Z0 ({Draw agreed, as after} 21. a5) (21. b5 $6 cxb5 22. axb5 a5 23. Ra1 Nd6 {, favours only Black Nc8} 24. Nf3 {Ncd6 , Black is fine but no more.}) 1/2-1/2

