1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Rc1 O-O 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Rxc3 c6 11. e3 Re8 ({Also possible is} 11... a5 12. Bd3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 Bg6 15. Ne5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qe7 {Denker, A-Fischer,R New York 1959.}) 12. Be2 a5 ({Equal is} 12... Bf5 13. Ne5 Nd7 14. Nxd7 Bxd7 15. O-O Qd6 {, but White should be careful and do not try the minority attack with} 16. b4 $6 a5 17. Qb3 axb4 18. axb4 {, as after} b5 $1 {(Botsari,A-Atalik,S Khalkida 1998) Black takes over the advantage, as the white b4-pawn is weaker than his c6 and the occupation of the a-file is rather pleasant.}) 13. O-O Bg4 ({White might get something after} 13... a4 14. Ne5 Nd7 15. f4 $14 {, as it is very difficult for Black to go for ...f6, which will create too many holes around his king.}) 14. b4 {The minority attack roles.} axb4 15. axb4 Nd7 16. Qb3 ({White should be careful, as the game of chess is not only referring to strategical concepts but also to tactical! After the naive} 16. b5 $6 {, Black replies with} c5 $1 {, achieving a better position:} 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bxe2 19. exf6 Bxd1 20. Rxd1 b6 $13 {.}) 16... b5 $1 {Stopping White's b5-advance and preparing ...Nb6-c4.} 17. Rfc1 Re6 $1 ({The correct set-up. Black must protect his pawn from the side, not self-pinning his rooks:} 17... Rec8 $2 18. Bxb5 $16 {.}) 18. Qb2 {White must hurry to exchange rooks in order to avoid falling in a passive position.} Bxf3 (18... Nb6 19. Ra3 Ree8 20. Rca1 Rxa3 21. Qxa3 Ra8 22. Qc3 Rxa1+ 23. Qxa1 {.}) 19. Bxf3 Nb6 20. Ra3 Ree8 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Ra1 Qd8 23. h3 {Draw agreed in an equal position.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "The Strategy Instructors Volume 1: Pawn "]
