1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 Be7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 g6 12. Bf4 Ne6 13. Be5 Ng7 14. Rab1 Bf5 15. b4 a6 16. a4 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 b5 18. Rfc1 Nf5 {White's minority attack which started with 15.b4, seems to have come to an end. Well, Black had to pay a price for it, as his c-pawn has become rather weak and it is a potential target. But in some way, also the white b4-pawn can be considered somewhat weak, as it needs a heavy piece to protect it.} 19. e4 $5 {A typical 'mechanism' to play against the b5-c6-d5 pawn structure is to break with 19.e4. In this case White is ‘stating’ that Black's c6-pawn will prove weaker than his d4-pawn.} dxe4 20. Nxe4 {Now White has an optimal pressure on the queenside and can claim an advantage.} Nxe4 ({Black might have considered} 20... bxa4 21. Rxc6 Nxe4 22. Qxe4 a3 23. g4 Nd6 24. Qd3 {( 24.Qd5 Nb5 25.Qc4 $14 )} Nb5 25. d5 Qd7 26. Qc4 Rad8 27. Rd1 $14 {.}) 21. Qxe4 Qd5 (21... f6 {, was possible, when} 22. g4 $1 {, would be strong:} fxe5 {( 22...Ng7 23.Bh2 $14 )} 23. gxf5 gxf5 24. Qxc6 {( 24.Qxf5 exd4 25.Rxc6 Rf8 26.Qe4 $14 )} Kh8 {( 24...e4?! 25.Qe6+ Kh8 26.Ne5 Qxd4 27.Kh1 $16 )} 25. axb5 axb5 26. dxe5 Rg8+ 27. Kh1 Ra2 28. Rg1 $1 Rxf2 29. Rxg8+ Qxg8 30. Rg1 $14 {.}) 22. Qxd5 cxd5 23. axb5 axb5 24. Rc6 $1 {A very important move that had to be foreseen around five moves ago. White stops an eventual ...f6 and prepares Rb6.} Ra2 25. Rb6 f6 $1 26. Bh2 (26. Bb8 {, would probably be a better move, to close the a8-square for the e8-rook, as after the move played, the fantastic manoeuvre ...Ra8-a3 was possible. After this move Black should get active with} Rc8 $1 27. Rxb5 Rcc2 28. Rf1 Rab2 29. Rxd5 Rxb4 $14 {.}) 26... Bxb4 $6 ({Black missed} 26... Rea8 $1 27. g4 {( 27.Rxb5 Ra1! 28.Rf1 Rxf1+ 29.Kxf1 Ra1+ 30.Ke2 Ra2+= ) (Or 27.Rf1!? Bxb4 28.Rxb5 Bc3 29.Rxd5 R2a4 30.g4 Nxd4 31.Kg2= )} R8a3 $1 {(this was really hard to foresee for Black after White's 26th move)} 28. gxf5 Rxf3 29. fxg6 Rfxf2 30. gxh7+ Kxh7 {.}) 27. g4 $1 Ba5 $2 (27... Nxd4 $1 {was a better choice:} 28. Nxd4 Bc5 29. Re6 Rxe6 30. Nxe6 Bxf2+ 31. Kf1 $14 {.}) 28. Ra6 $1 Ng7 29. Rxb5 Ra3 30. Kg2 Bb4 31. Rxa3 (31. Rxf6 Be7 32. Rc6 {was quite possible.}) 31... Bxa3 32. Rxd5 Be7 33. Ra5 $1 Rd8 34. d5 $1 Bb4 35. Rb5 Bc3 36. Kf1 $1 {White had won a healthy pawn and the rest was a matter of good technique.} h5 37. Ke2 hxg4 38. hxg4 Ra8 39. Rb3 Ba5 40. Nd4 Re8+ 41. Kd3 Be1 42. d6 $1 Rd8 43. Rb7 $1 Z0 ({Black resigned due to} 43... Ba5 {( 43...Bxf2 44.Rxg7+ Kxg7 45.Ne6+ Kg8 46.Nxd8+- )} 44. d7 Kf7 45. Nc6 {. White implemented a clear and common idea for these pawn structure formations.}) 1-0

