1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. Bd2 Qe7 12. cxd5 exd5 {A typical position to opt for the minority attack.} 13. b4 $1 Rad8 (13... Qxb4 $6 14. Nxd5 Qd6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Qxf6 Nxf6 17. Rab1 $16 {would only favour White.}) 14. Be1 ({The immediate advance of the b-pawn would be premature:} 14. b5 $6 c5 $1 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 cxd4 17. exd4 $2 {( 17.Rac1= )} Ne5 {is winning for Black. White is in no hurry and carefully prepares the b5 break, as Black cannot pose any immediate danger.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Rac1 Qe6 16. Qe2 Bf8 17. Qb2 b5 $5 {Black adopts one of the defensive mechanisms analysed earlier, as White was ready for the b5 advance.} 18. a4 a6 19. a5 {Preventing Black's standard ...Nb6-c4 idea and preparing to apply pressure on the backward c6-pawn.} Nh5 $1 {Looking for kingside counterplay by ...f5-f4; a typical idea.} 20. Rc2 f5 21. Ne2 Nb8 22. Bd2 Qd7 23. Nc1 Nf6 24. Bf1 Ne4 25. Nd3 Qe7 $6 (25... Nxd2 $2 26. Rdxd2 Rc8 27. g3 $14 {would not solve Black's problems.}) ({But} 25... Nd6 $1 {is essential - then the position is unclear with chances for both sides, and White would have to seek other plans.}) 26. Qc1 $1 Nd6 $2 ({Black's handling of the position and its problems had, up to this point, been successful. However, with her last move she allows White an excellent exchange sacrifice, after which her position becomes difficult. After the correct} 26... Rc8 $1 {, there would be all to play for.}) 27. Rxc6 $1 {An effective exchange sacrifice.} Nxc6 28. Qxc6 Qb7 {Otherwise, Black would lose another pawn.} 29. Qxb7 Nxb7 30. g4 $1 fxg4 31. hxg4 Nd6 32. Nc5 {For the sacrificed exchange White has obtained a pawn, the better pawn structure, two bishops and clear targets (a6 and d5). His position is preferable.} Ra8 33. Be1 $1 Ra7 34. Rd3 Kg7 35. Bg2 Ne4 36. f3 $1 Nxc5 ({White would have a decisive superiority after} 36... Nd6 37. Bg3 {, intending Be5 and f4.}) 37. dxc5 {Now a protected passed c-pawn has been added to White's advantages.} Rae7 38. Kf2 Kf7 39. f4 ({Also, quite good and 'better' for the time-trouble, was} 39. Bc3 $1 Bg7 40. Bxg7 Kxg7 41. f4 $16 {, with an easy win.}) 39... d4 40. Bd5+ Kf6 41. e4 Rxe4 $1 {Returning the exchange is Black’s best option and this action allows him to fight for a positive result.} 42. Bxe4 Rxe4 43. Rxd4 $1 ({Compulsory, as} 43. Bd2 $2 Ke6 $1 44. Kf3 Kd5 {, would have been satisfactory for Black.}) 43... Rxd4 44. Bc3 Ke6 45. Bxd4 Kd5 46. Be5 $6 (46. Bf6 $1 {was clearly preferable, with good winning chances. The excellent placement of the black king in the centre makes White's task very difficult.}) 46... g5 $1 47. Kf3 Bh6 48. Bf6 $1 gxf4 49. g5 Bf8 50. Kxf4 Ke6 51. Be5 Be7 52. Bd6 $2 {A grave blunder! It must however, be noted that both players had very little time at their disposal until the end of the game, with successive errors as a consequence.} (52. Bc3 Bf8 53. Kg4 Be7 54. Bf6 $1 Bf8 $1 {( 54...Bxf6 55.gxf6 Kxf6 56.Kh5+- )} 55. Bb2 Be7 56. Bg7 Bd8 57. Bf6 Bc7 58. Kh5 {, was good enough for the win.}) 52... Bd8 $2 ({This is even losing! The black bishop had to keep an eye on the h6-square, preventing the white king from invading. Losing control of the f8-square leaves Black unable to defend. But after all, Black had an easy win here by the simple} 52... Bxd6+ 53. cxd6 Kxd6 54. Kf5 Kd5 55. Kf6 {And now} Ke4 $1 {55...Kc4? 56.Kg7 Kxb4 57.Kxh7 Kxa5 58.g6+-} 56. Kg7 Kf5 57. Kh6 Kg4 58. g6 hxg6 59. Kxg6 Kf4 {.}) 53. Kg4 Kd5 54. Kh5 Kc4 ({Or} 54... Ke6 55. Kh6 Kd5 {( 55...Kf5 56.c6 Bxg5+ 57.Kh5! ( 57.Kxh7? Ke6 58.c7 Kd7= ) 57...Bd8 58.c7 Bxc7 59.Bxc7 Ke6 60.Kh6+- )} 56. Bf4 Ke4 57. Bc1 {.}) 55. c6 Kb3 {And Black lost in time, in a hopeless position. An interesting game with a lot of blunders by the way…} 1-0

