[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

{When White's b-pawn advances without being able to be exchanged, then it 'creates' some holes and leaves a number of unprotected squares on the queenside. Taking these facts into account, Black usually has enough compensation for his structural weakness.} 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Bd3 c6 11. O-O Ne4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. b4 Ndf6 ({Possible is} 13... a6 14. a4 Nb6 15. a5 {( 15.b5 cxb5 16.axb5 a5 $13 )} Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Nd7 17. Nd2 $14 {.}) 14. b5 c5 $1 15. dxc5 Nxc5 (15... Qxc5 $2 {is a blunder:} 16. Nxe4 Qxc2 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Bxc2 {.}) 16. Rac1 Nce4 $1 {Accurate.} (16... b6 17. Nd4 Bb7 18. a4 Rec8 19. Bf5 Ne6 20. Nc6 $1 Qd6 21. Ne2 $14 {Geller-Durao, Sochi 1977}) ({and} 16... Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Be6 18. Nd4 $14 {were proved quite nice for White.}) 17. Qb2 Bd7 {Time to take stock. White has succeeded in his minority attack and he has created an isolated weak black d-pawn to plan around it. On the other hand, Black should also be satisfied, as he has solved his opening problems more or less, except of course his weak pawn. But his well-placed and active pieces fully compensate it.} 18. h3 Rac8 19. Ne2 Nc5 (19... Rxc1 {, was possible:} 20. Qxc1 {( 20.Rxc1? Nxf2-+ )} Rc8 21. Qb2 Nc5 $13 {.}) 20. Bc2 Nce4 $6 ({Not so bad, but} 20... Rc7 $1 21. Nfd4 Rec8 $13 {, was more active.}) 21. a4 Ng5 22. Nfd4 Rc4 23. Nf4 Rec8 24. Bb3 R4c5 25. Rcd1 $6 ({Too optimistic. The natural continuation was} 25. Rxc5 Rxc5 {( 25...Qxc5? 26.Qa2 $16 )} 26. Nd3 Rc7 27. Rc1 $14 {.}) 25... Nge4 26. Nde2 Be6 27. Qd4 a6 28. Nd3 $6 (28. bxa6 bxa6 29. f3 Nc3 30. Nxc3 Rxc3 $13 {.}) 28... R5c7 29. b6 ({A blunder would be} 29. Rc1 $2 Nd2 $1) ({But} 29. Ndf4 {, was about equal.}) 29... Rc6 30. Ne5 Rc5 31. Nf4 (31. Nd3 Nc3 $1 32. Nxc3 Rxc3 $15 {.}) 31... Qd6 32. Ned3 $2 ({Here comes the blunder anyway! Forced was} 32. Rb1 {.}) 32... Rc3 $1 33. Ba2 a5 $6 (33... Ra3 $1 34. Qb2 Nc3 35. Ra1 Rxa4 {, was winning on the spot.}) 34. Ne5 R3c5 35. Ned3 Rc2 36. Ra1 (36. Bb3 R2c3 37. Ba2 Ra3 {.}) 36... Rd2 37. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 38. Rxd1 Nc3 39. Rd2 (39. Ra1 $2 Qa3 40. Nc1 Nxa2 41. Nxa2 Rc2 {.}) 39... Nfe4 40. Nxe6 fxe6 41. Rc2 Rc6 $1 {White is about to lose material - Black's pieces proved rather active and White never had any real 'annoying' plan.} 42. Ne5 (42. f3 Ng3 {.}) 42... Rc5 43. Nd3 Nb5 $1 44. Qb2 (44. axb5 $2 Rxc2 {.}) 44... Rxc2 45. Qxc2 Nbc3 46. f3 Ng3 $1 47. Kf2 (47. Qxc3 $2 Ne2+ {.}) 47... Nge2 48. Nf4 Qc6 $1 49. Ke1 (49. Nxe2 $2 Ne4+ {.}) 49... Nxf4 50. exf4 Qc5 (50... Qxb6 {, was playable too:} 51. Qxc3 Qg1+ 52. Kd2 Qxg2+ 53. Ke3 Qxa2 {.}) 51. Kf1 Ne4 $1 52. Qxc5 Nxc5 {White can resign as all his queenside pawns are ready to fall.} 53. f5 Kf7 54. Ke2 Nxa4 55. Kd3 Nxb6 56. fxe6+ Kxe6 57. Kd4 Kd6 58. f4 Nc4 59. g4 (59. Bxc4 dxc4 60. Kxc4 a4 61. g4 b5+ 62. Kb4 Kd5 {.}) 59... b5 60. g5 a4 61. h4 b4 62. f5 b3 0-1

