[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.co"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768] Not real attention was paid to the Capa's manoeuvre; the game thought to be a well-played one and that was all… The usual 'suspect', the 'Soviet School', took over and understood the importance of the manoeuvre for the QGD pawn structure (or Carlsbad as it is common to call it) and start often implementing it.} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qc2 g6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {Black has little to complain for his opening outcome; in general, he scores well from this position.} 11. Bh6 ({Another try is} 11. O-O O-O 12. h3 Re8 13. Bf4 Bf8 14. Ne5 Bg7 15. Bh2 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Ne4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nxe4 Rxe4 {Bu-Wei, Wuxi 2016.}) 11... Ng4 12. Bf4 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. h3 Ngf6 15. Ne5 Nb6 16. Bg5 Ne4 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qc2 Nd6 $1 {Of course, it is expected from the FIDE World Champion Petrosian to fully understand the pros & cons of the position. Black preserves his valuable knight and places it directly on d6.} 19. Na4 Nbc4 $1 {The good centralised white knight should be exchanged and not the edged one!} 20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Nc5 Nd6 {Black's strategy triumphed; he has no problems at all and he can start thinking of his kingside activity.} 22. Rac1 Qg5 23. Qd1 h5 24. Kh1 Re7 $1 {A good plan. Black will double rooks on the e-file or on his 2nd rank, preparing a well-timed invasion, depending on the coming situation.} 25. Nd3 Ne4 26. Nc5 Nd6 27. Nd3 Qf5 28. Ne5 f6 29. Nf3 Rg7 ({Not really bad, but it seems that} 29... g5 30. Nh2 Qg6 {was more accurate.}) 30. Nh2 Re8 31. Kg1 Ne4 32. Qf3 Qe6 $1 ({Black would be also in the driver's seat after} 32... Qxf3 33. Nxf3 g5 {, but there is no reason to exchange queens, as then his attack would lack steam.}) 33. Rfd1 g5 $1 {A good tactical shot.} 34. Qxh5 f5 $1 35. Re1 g4 36. hxg4 fxg4 37. f3 $6 ({Losing quickly, but even after} 37. Qh4 g3 38. fxg3 Nxg3 39. Rc2 Qg6 40. Rf2 Ne4 41. Rfe2 Ree7 $1 {, Black's attack is strong.}) 37... gxf3 38. Nxf3 (38. Qxf3 Rf8 39. Qe2 Ng3 40. Qd1 Qh6 {.}) 38... Rh7 39. Qe5 Qc8 $1 40. Qf4 Rf8 41. Qe5 Rf5 {And White resigned, as his queen is lost.} 0-1

