1. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768] The importance of preserving a knight (and the queen in most of the cases) on the board can be seen in the following game:} d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 c6 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qc2 g6 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 a5 13. Qc2 Re8 14. a3 Nb6 15. Na4 $6 ({This move looks really bad and it has to be bad. White has to opt for} 15. Ne5 Nfd7 16. Bxe7 Rxe7 17. Nxd7 Rxd7 18. Na4 Nc8 $13 {, as in Kaposztas,M-Szalai,K Hungary 2007.}) 15... Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Ne4 $1 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 {Black is ready to place his knight on d6 and then try his chances on both sides.} 18. Qc2 a4 19. Nd2 Nxd2 $6 {Of course, there was no point to this exchange, as the white knight has no real prospects.} (19... Nd6 20. Rbe1 Qd7 $15 {was the correct follow-up.}) 20. Qxd2 Qa5 21. Qc3 $1 Qxc3 22. bxc3 b5 23. Rfe1 f5 24. Kf1 Rf8 25. Ke2 {The endgame is equal and both sides cannot do much.} Kf7 ({Or} 25... f4 26. Kd3 f3 27. g3 {.}) 26. Kd3 Ke6 27. h4 Kd6 28. g3 h6 29. Rh1 Rfe8 30. Rbe1 Rc8 31. Rb1 Ke6 32. Rb2 Kd6 33. Rbb1 Rce8 34. Rbe1 Rc8 35. Rb1 Rce8 1/2-1/2

