1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Qc2 Na6 7. a3 Nc7 8. Bg5 g6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. b4 Ne4 14. Bf4 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $6 ({White should definitely take out Black's remaining knight via} 15. Bxc7 Qxc7 16. Qxc3 {. Probably he missed Black's clever sixteenth move.}) 15... Bd6 16. Bxd6 Nb5 $1 {Very clever. Now Black's knight gets to the ideal square and it becomes much easier for him to advance on the kingside than it is for White to make progress on the other flank.} 17. Qb3 Nxd6 18. a4 a6 ({A clear mistake would be} 18... a5 $6 19. b5 $1 cxb5 20. Qxd5 $13 {.}) 19. Ne5 $6 {The knight will get driven away from here via ...f7-f6.} (19. g3 {might have been a better plan, intending to reinforce White's king position with Nh4-g2. It would have been very difficult for Black to make progress after that but of course he will be the only one to have chances.}) 19... Re8 20. Rfe1 Qg5 21. h3 $6 (21. g3 {was better here too, not least because Black's breakthrough may come via ...f5-f4.}) 21... Kg7 22. Qc2 Re6 23. Rac1 Rae8 24. Qb1 ({And here} 24. Qd1 {was better, keeping the queen in contact with the kingside.}) 24... Qh5 $1 25. Qb3 {Black should be quite satisfied by the opening outcome and his middlegame prospects. White seems to have no active plan at his disposal, as his minority attack cannot progress. As a result of this, Black's hands on the kingside are free and as his pieces are well placed, his kingside pawns must start rolling. This can be done best by the ...f6, ...g5 and ...h5 structural formation.} f6 26. Nd3 ({It seems that White could put-up a more stubborn defence after} 26. Nf3 g5 27. Nh2 {, but this is not the case after} f5 $17 {.}) 26... g5 27. Qd1 Qg6 $1 {Of course! Black's queen will prove to be more useful than its counterpart.} 28. Qc2 R6e7 $1 29. Red1 ({Maybe White had to try} 29. Nc5 {, when Black should calmly retreat with} Qf7 {( 29...Qxc2 30.Rxc2 f5 31.Nd3 f4 32.Ne5 fxe3 33.fxe3 Nf7 34.Nxf7 Kxf7 35.b5 $15 ) (Or 29...f5 30.Nd3 f4 31.Ne5 $15 , should only help White).} 30. Nd3 h5 {, when the attack will grow strong.}) 29... h5 30. Qb1 ({After} 30. Ne1 {, Black would again avoid the exchange of queens with} Qh6 $1 {, in order to maintain his chances against White's king.}) 30... h4 31. Qc2 g4 32. Nf4 $2 ({This loses. White's best try was} 32. hxg4 Qxg4 33. Nf4 {, after which} Kh6 34. Kh2 Rg8 {, gives Black very dangerous attacking chances but nothing that's crystal clear.}) 32... Qxc2 {Now Black accepts the queen exchange, as he has a clear winning continuation to follow.} 33. Rxc2 g3 $1 34. Rd3 (34. fxg3 {is powerfully met by} Nf5 {.}) 34... Kh6 35. Kf1 Kg5 36. Ne2 $6 {In time-trouble White's resistance crumbles and we see the d6-knight make a decisive entrance.} (36. Re2 {, was best, though Black could then play} Ne4 37. f3 Nd6 {, intending 38...Nc4.}) 36... Nc4 $1 37. Rcc3 Nb2 38. Rd2 Nxa4 {The first pawn falls with more to follow.} 39. Rb3 Nb6 40. Ng1 ({Or} 40. fxg3 Nc4 {.}) 40... Nc4 41. Nf3+ Kh5 42. Rdd3 a5 $1 43. bxa5 Ra8 44. Rd1 Rxa5 45. Re1 b5 46. Re2 Ra1+ 47. Re1 Rea7 48. fxg3 Rxe1+ (48... hxg3 {would also have been good.}) 49. Kxe1 Ra1+ 50. Ke2 hxg3 51. Ne1 Ra2+ 52. Kd1 Rd2+ 53. Kc1 Re2 54. Kd1 Rxe3 55. Rxe3 Nxe3+ 56. Ke2 Nf5 57. Nc2 Nh4 58. Nb4 (58. Kf1 Kg5 59. Nb4 Kf4 60. Nxc6 Ke4 {would see Black's king make a decisive entrance.}) 58... Nxg2 59. Kf3 Nh4+ 60. Kxg3 Nf5+ 61. Kf4 Nxd4 62. Ke3 Nf5+ 0-1

