{Of course, Black is not always in the driver's seat but at least he can't complain about the opening outcome!} 1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nf3 O-O 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c6 12. O-O Nd7 13. a3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Nb6 {As already said, the 'QGD-Carlsbad' structure with only knights on the board is considered comfortable for Black. The present game doesn't change that evaluation but sheds light on some niceties.} 15. Ne5 Qf5 16. Rfc1 f6 17. Nd3 Nc4 18. Nc5 Nd6 19. Qc2 $1 {The exchange of the queens is essential for White's defence and by it he keeps an equal game.} Qxc2 ({In my opinion, Black should seriously consider} 19... Qh5 $13 {.}) 20. Rxc2 Rae8 21. g3 g5 {This move creates an object of attack for White (h2-h4).} (21... h5 {, was the main alternative.}) 22. Kg2 Kg7 23. a4 Re7 24. Rh1 Kg6 25. Rc3 h5 26. h4 Rh8 (26... g4 $5 {, keeps an equal game as the transfer of White's knight to f4 is harmless.}) 27. Rcc1 (27. hxg5 $5 fxg5 28. Nd3 Kf6 $13 {.}) 27... Rhh7 28. Rh2 Nf5 $6 (28... g4 {was still possible, with a completely dead-drawn position.}) 29. hxg5 fxg5 30. Nd3 g4 {Now the situation is completely different: the white knight has got the e5-square, and Black's h5-pawn is weak.} 31. Rch1 Kg5 32. Nf4 Ng7 (32... h4 $2 {should be completely out of the question:} 33. gxh4+ Rxh4 34. Rxh4 Nxh4+ 35. Rxh4 {.}) 33. b4 $1 {The 'two weaknesses rule'! White can be active on both sides of the board and this fact guarantees him the advantage.} a6 34. b5 axb5 35. axb5 Rh6 36. Ra1 Nf5 37. Ra8 h4 $5 (37... Rg7 $14 {, is possible but the text move gives White a seemingly attractive possibility.}) 38. gxh4+ (38. Rg8+ Rg7 39. Rxg7+ Nxg7 40. Rxh4 Rxh4 41. gxh4+ Kxh4 42. bxc6 bxc6 43. Ng6+ Kg5 44. Ne5 {, is hardly enough for a victory, e.g., after} Nh5 45. Nxc6 Kf5 {, but White could have considered it.}) 38... Nxh4+ 39. Rxh4 $5 ({A 'brilliant move' but Black miraculously holds his ground. Therefore} 39. Kf1 $14 {, maybe was better.}) 39... Kxh4 ({The alternative} 39... Rxh4 $5 40. Rg8+ Kf5 41. Ng6 Rhh7 42. Nxe7+ Rxe7 43. bxc6 bxc6 44. Kg3 {, looks bad but after the active} Rc7 $1 45. Rxg4 c5 46. Rf4+ Ke6 47. dxc5 Rxc5 {, Black should hold.}) 40. Rg8 (40. bxc6 bxc6 41. Rg8 Ra7 $13 {.}) 40... Rf7 41. f3 (41. bxc6 Rxc6 $1 {( 41...bxc6? 42.f3+- )} 42. Ng6+ Kh5 43. Ne5 Rf5 44. Nxc6 bxc6 {.}) 41... Rxf4 42. exf4 cxb5 $1 ({Again accurate, as} 42... gxf3+ $2 43. Kxf3 {, should be lost for Black:} cxb5 44. f5 b4 45. Kf4 b3 46. Rg1 {.}) 43. Rxg4+ (43. fxg4 Ra6 $1 44. f5 {( 44.Kf3 Ra3+ 45.Ke2 b4= )} b4 45. Kf3 Ra1 $1 46. Rh8+ Kg5 47. Rh5+ Kf6 48. Rh6+ Kg5 49. Rg6+ Kh4 50. Kf4 Rf1+ 51. Ke5 b5 $1 52. Rb6 Kxg4 53. f6 Kg5 {.}) 43... Kh5 44. Rg5+ Kh4 45. Rg7 $1 (45. Rxd5 $6 Rb6 $1 {.}) 45... Kh5 46. Rxb7 Ra6 47. Rxb5 Kh4 $1 48. Rb2 (48. Rxd5 Ra2+ 49. Kf1 Kg3 50. f5 Kxf3 51. Ke1 Ke4) ({Or} 48. Kf2 Ra2+ 49. Ke3 Ra3+ 50. Ke2 Ra2+ 51. Kd3 Ra3+ 52. Kc2 {( 52.Kd2 Kg3 53.f5 Kxf3= )} Rxf3 53. Rxd5 Kg4 54. Rd8 Kf5 $1 55. d5 Ke4 56. d6 Kd5 {.}) 48... Ra4 49. Rd2 Kh5 {Despite the two extra pawns, White can't strengthen his position.} 50. Kg3 Rb4 51. Rd1 Ra4 52. Kh3 Ra3 53. Rh1 Rd3 54. Kg3+ Kg6 55. Rh4 Rd2 56. Rg4+ Kf6 57. f5 1/2-1/2

